{"title_page": "Violence against Christians in India", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Anti-Christian violence in India}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n[[File:Adoration Mangalore.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Destroyed property inside Adoration Monastery, [[Mangalore]], after it was vandalised by activists belonging to the [[Bajrang Dal]], during the [[September 2008 attacks on Christians in Mangalore]]]]\n'''Anti-Christian violence in India''' is [[Religious violence|religiously-motivated violence]] against [[Christians]] in India.<ref name=\"HRW\" /> Violence against Christians has been seen by the organisation [[Human Rights Watch]] as a tactic used to meet political ends.<ref name=\"HRW\" /> The acts of violence include [[arson]] of [[Church (building)|churches]], [[Forced conversion|conversion of Christians by force]] and threats of physical violence, sexual assaults, murder of Christian priests and destruction of Christian schools, colleges, and cemeteries.<ref name=\"MANAS\">{{cite web|title=Anti-Christian Violence in India|url=http://www.sscnet.ucla.edu/southasia/History/Current_Affairs/Current_affairs.html|author=Vinay Lal|work=Manas: India and Its Neighbors|publisher=UCLA College of Letters and Science}}</ref><ref name=\"HRW\">{{cite web|title=Anti-Christian Violence on the Rise in India|url=http://hrw.org/english/docs/1999/09/30/india1626.htm|publisher=[[Human Rights Watch]]|date=29 September 1999 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090211152613/https://www.hrw.org/legacy/english/docs/1999/09/30/india1626.htm |archive-date=February 11, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2017, the [[United States Commission on International Religious Freedom|US Commission on International Religious Freedom]] (USCIRF) ranked India\u2019s persecution severity at \u201cTier 2\u201d along with [[Christianity in Iraq|Iraq]] and [[Christianity in Afghanistan|Afghanistan]].<ref name=chrtoday>{{cite web|last=Zylstra|first=Sarah Erkhoff|url=http://www.christianitytoday.com/news/2017/august/state-department-international-religious-freedom-report-irf.html |title=State Department's Unusually Short Religious Freedom Update: ISIS Is Bad|publisher=Christianity Today|date=August 2017|accessdate=August 28, 2017}}</ref> Over the past seven years, India has risen from No. 31 to No. 10 on [[Open Doors|Open Doors']] World Watch List, ranking just behind [[Christianity in Iran|Iran]] in persecution severity.<ref name=opendoors>{{cite web| url=https://www.opendoorsusa.org/christian-persecution/world-watch-list/india | title=World Watch List - India|date=|accessdate=January 31, 2018}}</ref><ref name=persupdate>{{cite web|last=Kaur|first=Surinder|url=http://www.persecution.in/node/4372|title=Police in Indian State of Uttar Pradesh Threaten and Extort Christian Families|publisher=Christian Persecution Update|date=July 4, 2017|accessdate=August 29, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170830235615/http://www.persecution.in/node/4372|archive-date=30 August 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2019, [[USCIRF]] repeatedly placed India as Tier-2 in minority persecution.<ref>https://www.uscirf.gov/sites/default/files/Tier2_INDIA_2019.pdf</ref>\n\n==Background==\nFrom 1964 to 1996, at least 38 incidents of violence against Christians were reported. In 1997, 24 such incidents were reported. Since 1998, Christians in India have faced a wave of violence.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news|title= Pope Lands in India Amid Rise in Anti-Christian Violence|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9807E4DA163AF935A35752C1A96F958260 | work=The New York Times | first=Alessandra | last=Stanley | date=6 November 1999 | accessdate=1 April 2010}}</ref> In 1998 alone, 90 incidents were reported.<ref name=\"MANAS\"/>\n\nA November 2001 survey by the [[National Commission for Minorities]](NCM) reported 27 attacks on Christian institutions and Christians in 1997, 86 instances in 1998, 120 instances in 1999 and 216 attacks in 2000. According to the NCM, the \"persecution\" of Christians had increased since the Bharatiya Janata Party came to power in 1998.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nIn 1999 a [[Human Rights Watch]] (HRW) report stated that [[Vishva Hindu Parishad]] (VHP), [[Bajrang Dal]], and [[Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh]] (the sister organisations of the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]]) are the most accused  organisations for violence against Christians in India.<ref name=\"HRW\" /> The [[National Commission for Minorities]] has alleged that the State governments ruled by the Bharatiya Janata Party and its allies provided support to the perpetrators.<ref name=\"ptinews.com\">{{cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/NCM-blames-Bajrang-Dal-for-Karnataka-Orissa-violence/articleshow/3509247.cms |title=NCM blames Bajrang Dal for Karnataka, Orissa violence |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=September 21, 2008 |publisher=[[The Times of India]] |access-date=July 30, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"mangalorean.com\">{{cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-karnataka/no-case-of-forcible-conversion-in-udupi-district-qureshi/article1340238.ece |title=No case of forcible conversion in Udupi district: Qureshi |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=September 18, 2008 |newspaper=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=July 30, 2018}}</ref> In 2001, the [[All India Christian Council]] reported that an attack against Indian Christians occurs every 36 hours.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nIn most reported cases the named perpetrators are members of the ''[[Sangh Parivar]]'' organisations. The ''Sangh Parivar'' are small subgroups that formed under the umbrella of the ''[[Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh]]'' (RSS), an umbrella organisation whose roots date back to 1925. The RSS, who promote a form of [[nationalism]], oppose the spread of \"foreign religions\" like [[Islam]] and [[Christianity]].<ref name=bauman>{{Cite book| publisher = Oxford University Press| isbn = 978-0-19-026631-8| last = Bauman| first = Chad M.| title = Pentecostals, Proselytization, and Anti-Christian Violence in Contemporary India| date = 2015-02-02 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DoFxBgAAQBAJ&pg=PT14}}</ref>  According to Human Rights Watch,  ''Sangh Parivar'' and local media were also involved in promoting anti-Christian propaganda in [[Gujarat]].<ref name=\"HRW\"/>  Mainstream [[Protestant]], [[Catholic]] and [[Orthodox Christianity|Orthodox]] Christians are targeted far less frequently than [[Evangelical]] and [[Pentecostal]] Christians.<ref name=bauman />\n\nMultiple news organisations reported an increase in incidents of violence against Christians after the new BJP government under [[Narendra Modi]] came to power after the [[2014 Indian general election|general election in April\u2013May 2014]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/politics/violence-against-christians-cong-slams-govt/article7004032.ece|title=Violence against Christians: Cong slams govt|website=thehindubusinessline.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/bearing-the-cross-of-communal-discord/article1-1326535.aspx|title=Bearing the cross: Recent attacks against Christians worrisome|date=15 March 2015|website=hindustantimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oneindia.com/india/churches-under-fire-a-list-of-recent-church-attacks-in-the-country-1685114.html|title=Churches under fire! A list of recent church attacks in the country|website=oneindia.com|date=16 March 2015}}</ref><ref name=indiatimes>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/articleshow/57055700.cms |title=Religious Minorities, Dalits Face Discrimination in India: Report|newspaper= The Economic Times|date=Feb 9, 2017| accessdate=August 29, 2017}}</ref> One investigation of crime records shows that church attack figures under NDA rule match those under UPA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Church-attack-figures-in-UPA-rule-match-those-under-NDA/articleshow/46830877.cms|title=Church attack figures in UPA rule match those under NDA - Times of India \u25ba|website=indiatimes.com}}</ref> In 2014 the Ministry of Home Affairs reported a \u201csteep 30 per cent rise in the number of communal violence incidents in 2013 as compared to 2012, with the maximum number of cases being reported from [[Uttar Pradesh]].\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/communal-incidents-up-by-30-up-tops-list/|title=Communal incidents up by 30%, UP tops list|date=2014-02-06|work=The Indian Express|access-date=2017-09-04|language=en-US}}</ref> Reported incidents of abuse carried out against Christians in India went up to 177 in 2015, and escalated to 300 in 2016, according to the Evangelical Fellowship of India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldea.org/news/4651/evangelical-fellowship-of-india-persecution-report-2015|title=Evangelical Fellowship of India Persecution Report 2015|website=www.worldea.org|language=en|access-date=2017-09-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180910153755/http://www.worldea.org/news/4651/evangelical-fellowship-of-india-persecution-report-2015|archive-date=10 September 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn a report by the Indian organisation Persecution Relief, the crimes against Christians increased by 60% from 2016 to 2019. There were 330 incidents in 2016, 440 incidents in 2017, 477 in 2018 and 527 incidents of hate crimes in 2019. The organisation reported there has been a direct link between [[Bharatiya Janata Party|Baratiya Janata Party]] gaining power in a state and increase in the attacks against Christians in the state.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalheraldindia.com/india/on-narendra-modi-watch-steep-rise-in-crime-against-christians-between-2016-and-2019|title=On Narendra Modi's watch, steep rise in crime against Christians between 2016 and 2019|website=National Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\nThe persecution of Christians in India increased sharply in the year 2016, according to a report by [[Open Doors]].<ref name=\"OpenDoors\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/jan/11/christians-in-india-increasingly-under-attack-study-shows|title=Christians in India increasingly under attack, study shows|first=Harriet|last=Sherwood|date=11 January 2017|website=the Guardian}}</ref> India was ranked 15th in the world in terms of danger to Christians, up from 31st four years earlier. According to the report, it is estimated that a church was burnt down or a cleric beaten on average 10 times a week in India in the year to 31 October 2016, a threefold increase on the previous year.<ref name=\"OpenDoors\" /> According to the [[All India Christian Council]], there was an attack on Christians recorded every 40 hours in India in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christianpost.com/news/violent-persecution-christians-india-attack-every-40-hours-report-182039/|title=Violent Persecution of Christians Rises in India, 'An Attack Being Recorded Every 40 Hours': Report|website=christianpost.com}}</ref> There were 26 documented cases of violence against Christians in the country between January and March 2016, while the central government refrained from speaking out against it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2016/03/14/christian-persecution-by-hindus-rises-in-india-say-humanitarian-groups.html|title=Christian persecution by Hindus rises in India, say humanitarian groups|first=Perry|last=Chiaramonte|date=14 March 2016|website=foxnews.com}}</ref> There were incidents of anti-Christian violence in Uttar Pradesh and Rajasthan around Christmas in December 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cruxnow.com/global-church/2016/12/30/christmas-attacks-confirm-threats-facing-christians-india/|title=Christmas attacks confirm threats facing Christians in India|date=30 December 2016|website=cruxnow.com}}</ref>\n\n==Overview of notable incidents==\n{{Quote box\n| quote = The Narendra Modi-led NDA government should award and provide legal and administrative protection to Hindus who attack churches across the country. Churches are no longer places of worship but factories for conversion of Hindus into Christianity,\n| source = - Munna Kumar Shukla, general secretary of the [[Hindu Mahasabha]] <ref name=\"shuklaquote\" />\n| align = right\n| width = 40em\n| bgcolor = #ffd2c7\n}}\nAccording to the [[BBC]], even though the [[National Commission for Minorities|National Commission for minorities]] and the [[Ministry of Home Affairs (India)|Ministry of Home Affairs]] report hundreds of cases of attacks against Christians per year, the number is certainly higher as Indian Journalists estimate that only 10% of the incidents are ever recorded.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Haynes, Jeffrey.|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/721900527|title=Religion, politics and international relations : selected essays|date=2011|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=|location=Abingdon, Oxon|pages=150|oclc=}}</ref>\n\nThe general secretary of the [[Hindu Mahasabha]], Munna Kumar Shukla, said that it is not illegal to attack a church and it violates no law and also said the organisation would award those who attack churches.<ref name=\"shuklaquote\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/church-attacks-not-illegal-hindu-outfit/article7127261.ece|title=Church attacks not illegal: Hindu outfit|date=2015-04-22|work=The Hindu|access-date=|url-status=live|language=|issn=}}</ref>\n\n=== Uttar Pradesh ===\nThe small Christian minority of 0.18% in the state of [[Uttar Pradesh]] with a population of 200 million, are the target of increasing violence.<ref name=\":0\" /> Citing an article by Institute for Leadership and Community Development, [[India Today]] lists Uttar Pradesh first among states of India which \u201ctend to have the greatest number of incidents of religiously-motivated attacks and communal violence.\u201d<ref name=indiatoday>{{cite web|last=Borgohain|first=Sonalee| url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/muslims-dalits-religious-attacks-grew-in-india-narendra-modi-us-report/1/879370.html |title=Attacks Against Muslims, Dalits Grew Sharply in India Under Modi: US Report|publisher=India Today|date=February 10, 2017| accessdate=August 28, 2017}}</ref> In the first half of 2016, there were more hate crimes against Christians in [[Uttar Pradesh]] than in any other state of India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldwatchmonitor.org/old-site-imgs-pdfs/4628515.pdf|title=Hate and Targeted Violence against Christians in India|last=|first=|date=August 2016|website=Evangelical Fellowship of India|access-date=August 31, 2017}}</ref> In a 2018 annual report, the Indian organisation Persecution Relief recorded 129 attacks against Christians in Uttar Pradesh alone, the highest among all states in India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/how-hindu-extremists-are-shutting-down-christian-churches-why-are-you-1360934|title=How Hindu extremists are shutting down Christian churches: 'Why are you worshipping a foreign god?'|last=Lal|first=Surinder Kaur|last2=EDT|first2=M. Clark On 3/26/19 at 8:33 PM|date=2019-03-26|website=Newsweek|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> The organisation also reported that there has been a direct link in increase in crimes with the rise of [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] in the state. In 2016, there were 39 incidents of hate crimes, but by 2019, the number increased to 109.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n{{Cquote|I will ensure that India is freed of Muslims and Christians by December 31, 2021\n| source = Rajeshwar Singh, Head of Dharm Jagran Samiti UP.<ref name=\":djs2021\" />\n| width = 30%\n| float = right\n}}\n\nOn December 2014, Rajeshwar Singh the head of the state's Dharm Jagran Samiti said:<blockquote>Our target is to make India a Hindu Rashtra by 2021. The Muslims and Christians don't have any right to stay here. So they would either be converted to Hinduism or forced to run away from here.<ref name=\":djs2021\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/dharm-jagran-samiti-leader-vows-to-create-hindu-rashtra-by-2021-231854-2014-12-19|title=Dharm Jagran Samiti leader vows to create Hindu rashtra by 2021|last=LucknowDecember 19|first=Piyush Srivastava|last2=December 19|first2=2014UPDATED|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18|last3=Ist|first3=2014 09:54}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nOn March 1998, Bajrang Dal militants chanting \"Jai Shri Ram\" attacked people with iron rods, burned down the tent, stole all the electronic-musical instruments and kidnapped a young man at a Christian assembly in [[Kanpur]]. Even the police threatened the Christians that they would not return the stolen property if they file an FIR. The ''[[Amar Ujala]]'' reported that the Bajrang Dal members also performed a \"naked dance\" in-front of the gathering.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sabrang.com/cc/comold/april98/sreport.htm|title=Saffron targets People of the Cross|last=|first=|date=April 1998|website=Communalism Combat|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn April 22, 2000, a priest and some nuns who were leading a group was surrounded and attacked by Bajrang Dal in [[Mathura]].<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ipsnews.net/2000/04/rights-india-church-called-for-talks-on-easter-attacks/|title=RIGHTS-INDIA: Church Called for Talks on Easter Attacks|last=|first=|date=Apr 27, 2000|website=Inter Press Service|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn August 2, 2015, a group of Hindutva fundamentalists disrupted a catholic prayer in [[Ghazipur]] and threatened the attendees to leave the area.<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.refworld.org/docid/57add86ec.html|title=Refworld {{!}} 2015 Report on International Religious Freedom - India|last=UNHCFR|first=|date=|website=Refworld|language=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, Christian families in Uttar Pradesh were beaten and denied water for their crops.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.express.co.uk/news/world/820571/christian-families-beaten-water-india-hindu-extremism-persecution|title=Christian families beaten and left without water in latest horrifying persecution|first=Katie|last=Mansfield|date=24 June 2017|website=express.co.uk}}</ref> On July 2019, members of the militant group [[Bajrang Dal]] allegedly beat up a pastor on suspicion of conversion in [[Kanpur]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsclick.in/rising-attacks-christians|title=Rising Attacks on Christians|date=2019-07-31|website=NewsClick|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> in March 2002, members of the RSS ransacked the Indian Missionary Society in Dhudia and attacked the clergy .<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.refworld.org/docid/3f7d4da823.html|title=Refworld {{!}} India: Treatment of Christians by Hindus, particularly the treatment of Christians who have converted from Hinduism; and the protection available to them|last=Refugees|first=United Nations High Commissioner for|website=Refworld|language=en|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\n=== Tamil Nadu ===\nThe annual 2018 report by the Indian Organization Persecution relief has ranked [[Tamil Nadu]] to be the 2nd state after Uttar Pradesh to record highest instances of attacks against Christians. 29 such instances were recorded in 2016, there were 57 instances in 2017 and 2018 recorded 67 incidents. The organisation reported that most of the attacks in the state were committed by [[Hindu Munnani]] members and their allied organisations.<ref name=\":0\" /> On May 2018, The [[Hindu Makkal Katchi]] president Arjun Sampath said that Christians and Muslims are not Tamil people.<ref name=\":arjunsampathquote\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibctamil.com/religion/80/100117?ref=recommended1?ref=fb|title=\u0bae\u0bc1\u0bb8\u0bcd\u0bb2\u0bbf\u0bae\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bc1\u0bae\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bbf\u0bb1\u0bbf\u0bb8\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bb5\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bc1\u0bae\u0bcd \u0ba4\u0bae\u0bbf\u0bb4\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bcd \u0b87\u0bb2\u0bcd\u0bb2\u0bc8\u0baf\u0bbe?|last=David|first=Niraj|date=2018-05-04|website=IBC Tamil|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n{{Cquote|Christians and Muslims are not Tamil people.\n| source = Arjun Sampath, President of Hindu Makkal Katchi.<ref name=\":arjunsampathquote\" />\n| float = right\n}}\nOn February 1998, the Bethany Fellowship Church was demolished and its participants were brutally attacked in [[Ayyampalayam, Erode]].<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/reports/1999/indiachr/christians8-05.htm|title=V. ATTACKS ACROSS THE COUNTRY|last=|first=|date=|website=Human Rights Watch|access-date=}}</ref> On October 1999, a Syrian Catholic church was set on fire near [[Kanyakumari]].<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sabrangindia.in/indepth/attacks-minorities-unrelenting|title=Attacks on minorities unrelenting|date=1999-11-01|website=SabrangIndia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn October 2008, During the [[2008 attacks on Christians in southern Karnataka]] the police reported 20 graves in a cemetery were desecrated in a district south of chennai, three churches were stoned in the districts of Karur and Erode, bibles in the outer walls of Chennai and Coimbatore were damaged, a statue of Mother Mary was stolen in Krishnagiri, a Virgin Mary icon was damaged in Kanyakumari and an idol of Jesus in Madurai was vandalised.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/latest-headlines/story/4-held-in-tamil-nadu-for-attacking-christian-institutions-31285-2008-10-09|title=4 held in Tamil Nadu for attacking Christian institutions|last=ChennaiOctober 9|first=Indo-Asian News Service|last2=October 9|first2=2008UPDATED|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-03-03|last3=Ist|first3=2008 20:37}}</ref> Four members belonging to the [[Hindu Munnani]] were arrested on October 9 and the number reached 22 on the next day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/latest-headlines/story/22-arrested-in-tamil-nadu-for-desecrating-christian-institutions-31362-2008-10-10|title=22 arrested in Tamil Nadu for desecrating Christian institutions|last=ChennaiOctober 10|first=Indo-Asian News Service|last2=October 10|first2=2008UPDATED|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-03-03|last3=Ist|first3=2008 20:09}}</ref>\n\nMembers of the [[Hindu Makkal Katchi]] vandalised a prayer hall, broke all the glass windows, damaged the furniture and disposed the prayer books in Coimbatore on January 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/coimbatore/Church-authorities-seek-police-protection/articleshow/11547861.cms|title=Church authorities seek police protection {{!}} Coimbatore News - Times of India|last=Jan 19|first=TNN {{!}} Updated|last2=2012|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16|last3=Ist|first3=05:51}}</ref>\n\nOn January 28, 2016, A mob of around 35 Hindu nationalists attacked a catholic priest and 3 other church officials in their car in [[Ettimadai]]. They were punched, kicked and attacked with granite stones.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/world/christian-persecution-by-hindus-rises-in-india-say-humanitarian-groups|title=Christian persecution by Hindus rises in India, say humanitarian groups|last=Chiaramonte|first=Perry|date=2016-03-10|website=Fox News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> The mob then dragged them, beat them and made them walk for 2.5 kilometres in a national highway. During the incident the police refused to intervene and stood there idly. All the victims were hospitalised and the priest was left unconscious.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mattersindia.com/2016/02/mob-attacks-priest-catholics-in-coimbatore/|title=Mob attacks priest, Catholics in Coimbatore|date=2016-02-01|website=Matters India|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mattersindia.com/2016/02/bishops-demand-probe-into-coimbatore-mob-attack/|title=Bishops demand probe into Coimbatore mob attack|date=2016-02-01|website=Matters India|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> On March 2016, a mob of Hindu Munnani members vandalised a newly built CSI church in [[Kalapatti]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/coimbatore/Church-attack-Hindu-Munnani-members-protest-against-arrest/articleshow/51433259.cms|title=Church attack: Hindu Munnani members protest against arrest {{!}} Coimbatore News - Times of India|last=Mar 17|first=TNN {{!}} Updated|last2=2016|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24|last3=Ist|first3=01:13}}</ref>\n\nHindu Makkal Katchi's Tirunelveli district president and the secretary locked up a girls school run by catholic nuns because they were supporting the anti-[[National Eligibility cum Entrance Test (Undergraduate)|NEET]] agitations on September 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/hindu-makkal-katchi-men-held-for-locking-up-christian-school-tirunelveli/article19678082.ece|title=Hindu Makkal Katchi men held for locking up Christian school|date=2017-09-13|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-17|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\nAround 25 members allegedly belonging to the [[Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh|RSS]] and [[BJP]] desecrated a prayer hall and attacked the worshippers during the Christmas celebrations on December 2017 in Coimbatore. The pastor suffered a head injury, a woman suffered a fracture and others had minor injuries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/rss-members-allegedly-vandalise-prayer-hall-coimbatore-decked-christmas-72906|title=RSS members allegedly vandalise prayer hall in Coimbatore decked up for Christmas|last=|first=|date=|website=The News Minute|access-date=}}</ref> A local BJP leader and three others were arrested.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/tamil-nadu-news/coimbatore-bjp-leader-arrested-in-attack-on-christian-prayer-hall-cops-1785772|title=Coimbatore BJP Leader Arrested In Attack On Christian Prayer Hall: Cops|website=NDTV.com|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> On May 2017, Hindu Munnani members were alleged of attacking a Church three times in the month in [[Sulur]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/take-action-hindu-munnani-church-attack-christians-threaten-return-ration-cards-61869|title='Take action on Hindu Munnani for Church attack': Christians threaten to return ration cards|last=|first=|date=|website=The News Minute|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nAround 30 members of the [[Hindu Munnani]] ransacked a prayer hall in Madurai on March 11, 2018. They burned bibles, attempted to strip the pastor's wife naked and threatened to kill the pastor's family if they did not close down the prayer hall.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/tamil-nadu-news/3-christian-prayer-halls-vandalised-in-madurai-since-sunday-1823531|title=3 Christian Prayer Halls Vandalised In Madurai Since Sunday|website=NDTV.com|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref> The attackers then went to three other Pentecostal halls and threatened them of attacks if they were not shut in a week.<ref>{{Cite news|last=B.a|first=Pon Vasanth|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Madurai/hindu-right-wing-group-vandalises-prayer-home-madurai/article23041946.ece|title=Hindu right wing group vandalises prayer home|date=2018-03-11|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-08|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/madurai/minority-commissioner-talks-to-pastors/articleshow/63323846.cms|title=Minority commissioner talks to pastors {{!}} Madurai News - Times of India|last=Mar 16|first=TNN {{!}} Updated|last2=2018|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-03-08|last3=Ist|first3=11:15}}</ref>\n\nMembers belonging to the RSS attacked an ex-BJP man who converted to Christianity with a [[sickle]] in Coimbatore on April 2018. The man was hospitalised due to Head and neck injuries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/coimbatore/rss-workers-attack-ex-bjp-man-who-converted-to-christianity/articleshow/63837542.cms|title='RSS workers' attack ex-BJP man who converted to Christianity {{!}} Coimbatore News - Times of India|last=Apr 20|first=TNN {{!}}|last2=2018|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18|last3=Ist|first3=00:51}}</ref>\n\nOn July 2019, residents in the Alagumalai village of Tirupur district accused the Hindu Munnani of creating religious tensions after the outfit built an iron fence on a concrete road to block a way used by mostly Christian dalits.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsclick.in/dalit-residents-discriminated-untouchability-fence-tirupur-district|title=Dalit Residents Discriminated with Untouchability Fence in Tirupur District|date=2019-06-12|website=NewsClick|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> On August 2019, a mob of Hindu Munnani members attacaked a group of 40 Christian pilgrims, tore their posters, verbally abused them and accused the pilgrims of preaching Christianity in Velankanni.The local DSP said the pilgrims were not preaching and attackers were fanatics with no motive.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/hindu-munnani-members-held-assaulting-pilgrims-walking-velankanni-church-107603|title=Hindu Munnani members held for assaulting pilgrims walking to Velankanni Church|last=Thirumurthy|first=Priyanka|date=21 August 2019|website=The News Minute|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Delhi===\nOn September 1998, a St. Bernard statue was chopped and thrown out of the campus in [[Jesus and Mary College]],.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nOn December 2014, the [[St. Sebastian's Church (Dilshad Garden)]] was set ablaze by unidentified men which reduced the entire interior to ashes.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Perappadan|first=Bindu Shajan|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Delhi/archbishop-writes-to-pm-wants-judicial-inquiry/article6654061.ece|title=Dilshad garden church attack: Archbishop seeks judicial inquiry|date=2014-12-02|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-21|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> A forensic team reportedly found traces of kerosene. Later, the [[Aam Aadmi Party]] accused the police of ignoring clear evidence of arson.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/delhi-news/protests-after-fire-in-delhi-church-police-investigate-possible-arson-707034|title=Protests After Fire in Delhi Church, Police Investigate Possible Arson|website=ndtv.com}}</ref> On December 2014, unknown assailants threw stones and broke the windows at Our Lady of Fatima Forane Church during the evening mass at South Delhi.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india/two-held-for-vandalising-vikaspuri-church/story-2YY8ivPZxWy7XoEJEQv07M.html|title=Two held for vandalising Vikaspuri church|date=2015-01-15|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\nOn January 2015, Two unidentified men vandalised a church in [[Vikaspuri]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/church-vandalised-in-west-delhis-vikaspuri-area-235729-2015-01-15|title=Church vandalised in West Delhi's Vikaspuri area|last=DelhiJanuary 15|first=Mail Today Bureau New|last2=January 15|first2=2015UPDATED|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-03-21|last3=Ist|first3=2015 05:03}}</ref> On February 2015, Unidentified men broke open the St. Alphonsa church's main gate in Vasant Kunj and ransacked its premises.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/assembly-delhi/church-in-delhi-vandalised-five-days-before-assembly-elections-reports-736306|title=Church in Delhi Allegedly Vandalised 5 Days Before Assembly Elections|website=NDTV.com|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\nOn February 2015, a catholic school was vandalised and the principal's office ransacked in Vasant Vihar. The Archdiocese spokesperson Sankar said that 5 churches have been attacked since December 2014 allegedly by fundamentalist groups to instill fear among the community.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/christian-school-vandalized-in-delhi-442075.html|title=Christian school vandalized in Delhi|date=2015-02-13|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, St. Mary's Church in [[Agra]] was vandalised and statues of [[Mother Mary]] and the [[Infant Jesus]] were damaged.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/church-vandalised-in-agra-mother-mary-s-statues-knocked-over/article1-1337771.aspx|title=Agra church vandalised, Mother Mary idol damaged|date=16 April 2015|website=hindustantimes.com}}</ref> Police arrested a Muslim man who reportedly was angry about being rejected by a Christian girl.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Spurned-lover-attacked-Agra-church-Cops/articleshow/47033360.cms|title=Spurned lover attacked Agra church: Cops - Times of India \u25ba|website=indiatimes.com}}</ref>\n\nOn May 5, 2018 St. Stephen's college chapel was vandalised. The Chapel's door and the cross outside were desecrated with pro-Hindutva slogans.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/delhi-news/there-should-be-a-temple-here-vandalism-hits-st-stephens-college-chapel-1847663|title=\"There Should Be A Temple Here\": Vandalism Hits St Stephen's College Chapel|website=ndtv.com}}</ref>\n\n===Jammu and Kashmir===\n{{Rquote|right|The anti-Christian intolerance in Jammu and Kashmir is reaching alarming proportions.|Sajan George, The president of the Global Council of Indian Christians (GCIC)<ref name=autogenerated3>{{cite web|last=Gheddo |first=Piero |url=http://www.asianews.it/news-en/Indian-Kashmir,-two-Christians-arrested-on-false-charges-of-forced-conversions-27639.html |title=INDIA Indian Kashmir, two Christians arrested on false charges of forced conversions - Asia News |publisher=Asianews.it |date= |accessdate=2013-05-13}}</ref>}}\nChristians in India have frequently been subjected to intolerance,<ref name=autogenerated3 /> harassment, intimidation, and attacks by Muslims.<ref name=autogenerated6>{{cite web|last=Gheddo |first=Piero |url=http://www.asianews.it/news-en/Kashmir,-false-accusations-on-Facebook:-mob-tries-to-lynch-12-tourists-27053.html |title=INDIA Kashmir, false accusations on Facebook: mob tries to lynch 12 tourists - Asia News |publisher=Asianews.it |date= |accessdate=2013-05-15 |quote=The violent reaction was triggered by a [https://m.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=420992237981036&id=100002107914756&set=a.114711591942437.22089.100002107914756&ref=stream&_rdr photo] published on the Facebook page Gulmarg News.}}</ref> In [[Jammu and Kashmir]], a Christian convert and missionary, Bashir Tantray, was killed, allegedly by militant Islamists in 2006.<ref>[http://www.speroforum.com/site/article.asp?id=6705 Christian convert from Islam shot dead in Kashmir] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071017021324/http://www.speroforum.com/site/article.asp?id=6705 |date=17 October 2007 }},''SperoNews''.</ref>\n\nThe Government of Jammu-Kashmir in 2010 asked Jim Borst, a Dutch Catholic [[missionary]], who was at that time one of the two members of the Institute Mill Hill missionary in the Kashmir valley, to leave the valley. Borst was also in charge of two schools there.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gheddo |first=Piero |url=http://www.asianews.it/news-en/Missionary-forced-to-leave-Kashmir-because-his-schools-are-too-good-18910.html |title=INDIA Missionary forced to leave Kashmir because his schools are \"too good\" - Asia News |publisher=Asianews.it |date= |accessdate=2013-05-13}}</ref> Nevertheless, the spokesperson for Indian Christians, John Dayal rejected the claim that any forced conversion took place. John Dayal stated that a fact finding team interviewed Church personnel, the police, Ulema, school authorities and found no evidence of force or fraud conversions and each baptism has been proved to be voluntary\".<ref name=autogenerated5>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Fatwa-announced-against-Christian-schools-in-Kashmir-3-priests-asked-to-leave-valley/articleshow/11555784.cms |title='Fatwa' announced against Christian schools in Kashmir, 3 priests asked to leave valley - The Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date= |accessdate=2013-05-13}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2012, a [[Sharia]] court of Kashmir announced a [[Fatwa]] against Christian schools in Kashmir. It asked three priests to leave the valley on the charge that they were \"luring Muslims to Christianity\". The court not only instructed the government of Jammu and Kashmir to monitor such activities in the future but to also take over the management of the Christian missionary schools.<ref name=autogenerated5 />\n\nIn April 2012, a Christian couple was arrested with that accusation of \"promoting enmity\". The policemen later explained that the arrest was made \"as a precaution to prevent tensions in the area.\" However, their children told a completely different tale: \"Our parents went to Srinagar on April 16 last year to attend a wedding. The next day, while doing some shopping at the market, talking to a salesman our father said he was Christian and they were insulted, beaten and finally arrested by local police.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Gheddo |first=Piero |url=http://www.asianews.it/news-en/Indian-Kashmir:-Christians-arrested-for-promoting-enmity-24554.html |title=INDIA Indian Kashmir: Christians arrested for \"promoting enmity\" - Asia News |publisher=Asianews.it |date=2012-04-20 |accessdate=2013-05-13}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2012, unidentified arsonists, believed to be Muslim, [[church arson|set fire to a Catholic church]].<ref name=autogenerated4>{{cite web|last=Gheddo |first=Piero |url=http://www.asianews.it/news-en/Indian-Kashmir,-Muslims-set-fire-to-a-Catholic-church-24848.html |title=INDIA Indian Kashmir, \"unknown arsonists\" set fire to a Catholic church - Asia News |publisher=Asianews.it |date=2012-05-25 |accessdate=2013-05-13}}</ref>\n\nIn Srinagar, [[All Saints Church, Srinagar|All Saints Church]], a United Protestant parish belonging to the [[Church of North India]], and its parsonage, as well as the home of a Christian lady was also burned.<ref name=\"Singh2002\">{{cite web |last1=Singh |first1=Manpreet |title=India: Christians reach out to war-weary Muslims in Kashmir |url=https://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2002/september9/12.26.html |publisher=[[Christianity Today]] |accessdate=18 March 2020 |language=English}}</ref>\n\nConcerning these issues Father Mathew Thomas, pastor of Holy Family commented \"With these gestures, the Muslim community is trying to intimidate the Christian minority. But there are not even 400 Christians in Srinagar: I appeal to Omar Abdullah, chief minister, a Muslim who studied in Christian institutions. He must protect the entire population of Srinagar, including minorities.\"<ref name=autogenerated4 />\n\nA Muslim mob with the imprimatur of the local Imam, in April 2013, attacked a group of seven British Christians consisting of five women and two children, who were living in Shivpora for about four years. Stones were hurled at their vehicles and their house. The reason they claimed was to stop conversions to Christianity.<ref name=autogenerated3 />\n\nOn 5 February 2013, a crowd of people threw stones at the walls of the hotel where eight Americans and four South Koreans, who were accused of forcing conversion through a [[Facebook]] page, were staying. There were no injuries.<ref name=autogenerated6 /> The Facebook page of Gulmarg News showed an image of three oriental women and first line of a long caption stated, \"Attention Kashmir!!! Islam in Kashmir is under attack, Christians trying to convert Muslims.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asianews.it/news-en/Kashmir,-false-accusations-on-Facebook:-mob-tries-to-lynch-12-tourists-27053.html|title=Kashmir, false accusations on Facebook: mob tries to lynch 12 tourists|last=AsiaNews.it|website=www.asianews.it}}</ref>\n\n===Madhya Pradesh===\nOn 25 February 1995, [[Mariam Vattalil|Sister Rani Maria]], a [[nun]] working within the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Indore|Diocese of Indore]] was stabbed to death, allegedly for [[proselytising]] the tribals of Madhya Pradesh.<ref>{{cite news | title='We forgive you': How a Kerala nun's family embraced her murderer | url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/we-forgive-you-how-a-nun-s-family-embraced-her-murderer/story-DxwvsFds9KhtUoK7IHMN5I.html | date=2 August 2017 | work=[[Hindustan Times]]}}</ref>\n\nOn September 23, 1998, a group of about 18 or 20 armed men barged into a convent and [[Jhabua nuns rape case|gang raped four nuns in Jhabua]]. Christian groups accused religious fundamentalists for the attack. Later, the Vishva Hindu Parishad, accused the nuns of religious conversion. The former BJP MP, head of the Bajrang Dal and deputy head of the VHP, Baikunt Lal Sharma Prem said that the nuns were asking for it.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nA church was burned down and bibles were burnt in [[Mandla district]] in September 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bhopal/Church-set-ablaze-in-Mandla-district/articleshow/43715586.cms |title=Church set ablaze in Mandla district |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=September 28, 2014 |publisher=The Times of India |access-date=July 30, 2018}}</ref> In March 2015, a Bible convention was attacked in [[Jabalpur]], with allegations that religious conversions were taking place.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/church-attacked-in-jabalpur-christians-threaten-to-shut-down-schools-if-attackers-not-caught-748560 |title=Church Attacked in Jabalpur, Christians Threaten to Shut Schools if Attackers Not Caught |last=Das |first=Siddarth Ranjan |date=March 22, 2015 |publisher=[[NDTV]] |access-date=July 30, 2018}}</ref> Christian tribals were said to be living in fear with the rising incidence of attacks.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/fear-rules-in-tribal-pockets-of-madhya-pradesh-after-attack-on-churches-749343 |title=Fear Rules in Tribal Pockets of Madhya Pradesh After Attack on Churches |last=Das |first=Siddarth Ranjan |date=March 25, 2015 |publisher=NDTV |access-date=July 30, 2018}}</ref> On March 2020, A Pentecostal pastor was attacked with rods,chains and sticks and left with multiple fractures and head injuries in [[Sehore]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/madhya-pradesh-man-assaulted-over-forced-conversion-6307493/|title=Madhya Pradesh: Man assaulted over 'forced conversion'|date=2020-03-10|website=The Indian Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\nOn March 2015, Around 50 members belonging to Bajrang Dal and Dharam Sena attacked a church and two schools with slogans of \"Jai Shree Ram\" in Jabalpur. They vandalised the church's parish house,destroyed the pots and window panes and also attacked the people who had gathered there for a convention.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/church-catholic-school-christians-jabalpur-valdalised-bajrang-dal-245392-2015-03-22|title=Church, Catholic school vandalised in Madhya Pradesh|last=DelhiMarch 22|first=IndiaToday in New|last2=March 25|first2=2015UPDATED|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-03-21|last3=Ist|first3=2015 10:27}}</ref> More than a dozen people were injured and one was left critical by the attack.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/bhopal/mp-three-churches-attacked-in-jabalpur-police-inaction-irks-christians/article1-1329370.aspx|title=MP: Church, two schools attacked in Jabalpur|date=22 March 2015|website=hindustantimes.com}}</ref> The same cathedral had also been attacked by right-wing groups in 2008 and the entire altar was burnt down.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zeenews.india.com/news/madhya-pradesh/jabalpur-church-targeted-for-second-time-since-2008_1566379.html|title=Jabalpur church targeted for second time since 2008|date=23 March 2015|website=india.com}}</ref>\n\nOn December 2017, members of the militant group [[Bajrang Dal]] attacked a group of catholic carol singers in [[Satna district]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thelogicalindian.com/news/right-wing-hindu-group-attack-carol-singers-satna-sets-priests-car-ablaze/|title=MP: Police Arrest 30 Carol Singers Singing On The Road, Right Wing Group Sets Priest's Car Ablaze|last=Mondal|first=Swarnami Mondal|date=2017-12-16|website=thelogicalindian.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref> The police detained the carol singers instead of the perpetrators and then the attackers attacked the Christian students inside the police station and set fire to the priest's car outside.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sputniknews.com/asia/201712151060037235-carol-singers-india-arrested/|title=Christmas Carol Singers Arrested in India, Priests Under Attack From Hindu Mob|website=sputniknews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref>\n\n===Kerala===\n\nA Christian priest, K. K. Alavi in [[Manjeri]], a 1970 convert from Islam,<ref>\"[http://www.the-good-way.com/eng/books/7825/format-pdf IN SEARCH OF ASSURANCE]\" by K. K. Alavi</ref> thereby raised the ire of his former Muslim community and received many death threats. An Islamic group named \"The [[NDF India|National Development Front]]\" actively campaigned against him.<ref name=CE>[http://www.christianexaminer.com/Articles/Articles%20Jan06/Art_Jan06_07.html Convert from Islam in India Remains on Death List] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130511041409/http://www.christianexaminer.com/Articles/Articles%20Jan06/Art_Jan06_07.html |date=11 May 2013 }},'''Christian Examiner'''</ref> Muslim clerics are known to hold up Alavi as a prime example of an enemy of Islam even during prayers.<ref name=CE/> In that area traditional Christianity is considered blasphemy.<ref name=CE/>\n\nIn April 1998, a Church was attacked and its crucifix desecrated.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nOn June 14, 2015, around 30 RSS activists attacked two Pentecostal Churches in [[Attingal]]. The first attack injured the pastor and five others and the second attack injured ten congregants including a physically disabled person.<ref name=\":14\" />\n\nIn 2010, members of [[Popular Front of India]](PFI) [[Assault on T. J. Joseph|chopped off the hand of Professor T.J. Joseph]]. PFI alleged Joseph of committing blasphemy against [[Mohammed|prophet Mohammed]], based on a question paper he prepared for an exam.<ref>{{cite news|author=Special Correspondent |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/states/kerala/article536784.ece |title=No report yet on 'Taliban-model' courts: Kodiyeri |newspaper=The Hindu |date=2010-07-28 |accessdate=2013-05-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://newindianexpress.com/cities/kochi/article164133.ece |title=Controversial lecturer's palm chopped off |work=The New Indian Express |date=5 July 2010 |accessdate=12 May 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mathrubhumi.com/english/news.php?id=94349 |title=Attackers cut off Newman college prof Joseph's hand |publisher=Mathrubhumi |date=4 July 2010 |accessdate=12 May 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716073428/http://www.mathrubhumi.com/english/news.php?id=94349 |archivedate=16 July 2011 }}</ref> According to police, the attack was carried out by an eight-member team consisting of Savad of [[Asamannoor]], Pareeth of North Vazhakkulam, Shobin of [[Kothamangalam, Ernakulam|Kothamangalam]], Nazar of [[Aluva]], Shajil of [[Muvattupuzha]], Shamsuddin of [[Perumbavoor]], Shanvas and Jamal.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.manoramaonline.com/cgi-bin/MMOnline.dll/portal/ep/malayalamContentView.do?articleType=Malayalam+News&contentId=7767812&contentType=EDITORIAL&BV_ID=@@@ |title=Home |publisher=Manorama Online |accessdate=12 May 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120307175130/http://www.manoramaonline.com/cgi-bin/MMOnline.dll/portal/ep/malayalamContentView.do?articleType=Malayalam+News&contentId=7767812&contentType=EDITORIAL&BV_ID=@@@ |archive-date=7 March 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Karnataka===\n{{see also|2008 attacks on Christians in southern Karnataka}}\n\nOn July 17, 1998, The Bajrang Dal militants carried out a series of attacks against eleven Christian schools in various parts of Karnataka.<ref name=\":9\" /> On November 22, 1998, RSS activists beat up the pastor and the worshipers of an Evangelical Church during a prayer service in [[Kulai (Suratkal)]].<ref name=\":9\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.csw.org.uk/1998/12/01/press/6/article.htm|title=India: Church latest target of violence in Indian state of Karnataka.|website=www.csw.org.uk|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> On November 1999, girls from the [[St. Joseph's Evening College, Bangalore|St. Joseph\u2019s Evening College,Bangalore]] were surrounded and physically attacked by a  local BJP MLA's supporters near [[Anekal]].<ref name=\":11\" />\n\nOn February 2002, Around 70 Hindutva nationalists armed with clubs and stones attacked the Holy Family Catholic Church in southern Karnataka which left several worshippers injured.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ecoi.net/en/document/1153247.html|title=Treatment of Christians by Hindus, particularly the treatment of Christians who have converted from Hinduism; and the protection available to them [IND39529.E]|last=Canada|first=Immigration and Refugee Board of|date=2002-09-12|website=www.ecoi.net|language=en|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\nThere was a wave of church bombings in the early 2000s by the once banned Islamic organisation [[Deendar Anjuman]] which alleged that Christianity was not an 'Indian' religion.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2008-11-28/bangalore/27920961_1_blasts-church-j-j-nagar | work=The Times Of India | title=Church blasts culprits may be sentenced today - The Times of India}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, there was a wave of attacks directed against [[Christian churches]] and prayer halls in [[Karnataka]] by the Hindu organisation [[Bajrang Dal]] around 2008.<ref>[http://archive.deccanherald.com/Content/Sep192008/scroll2008091990873.asp?section=frontpagenews UPA govt puts State on notice] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131226223258/http://archive.deccanherald.com/Content/Sep192008/scroll2008091990873.asp?section=frontpagenews |date=December 26, 2013 }} Deccan Herald - 19 September 2008</ref><ref>[http://www.deccanherald.com/content/21327/adoration-monastery-attack-pre-planned.html \u2018Adoration Monastery attack was pre-planned\u2019] ''[[Deccan Herald]]'' - 25 August 2010</ref> The violence started from 14 September 2008 when about 20 churches were vandalised in [[Mangalore]], [[Udupi]], [[Chikkamagaluru]], and in other districts of Karnataka.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.asianews.it/news-en/Karnataka:-20-churches-attacked,-Christians-accuse-police-of-inaction-13221.html|title=INDIA Karnataka: 20 churches attacked, Christians accuse police of inaction|last=AsiaNews.it|website=www.asianews.it|access-date=2016-03-06}}</ref> Minor violence was later reported from the border state of [[Kerala]]. [[B.S. Yeddyurappa]], the [[Chief Minister]] of Karnataka, said the attacks were provoked by conversions of [[Hindus]] to [[Christianity]]. He also alleged that a [[Protestant]] group had distributed literature which insulted Hindu gods. The Chief Minister however clarified that he was not defending the actions of those who attacked prayer halls and churches in Mangalore, Udupi and Chikmagalur on Sunday.<ref name=\"More church attacks in Karnataka\">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7621590.stm More church attacks in Karnataka] BBC - 17 September 2008</ref> Later, the Christian leaders denied it and commented that [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] (BJP) was inciting violence rather than working to calm the situation. On the other hand, the Central Government had strongly criticised and sent showcase notices to the state Government for not solving the issue effectively.<ref>[http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2008\\story_20-9-2008_pg4_13 India government warns state over anti-Christian attacks] {{dead link|date=February 2017|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}} Daily Times - 20 September 2008</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.asianews.it/news-en/Karnataka:-New-wave-of-violence-and-attacks-on-Christians.-Complicity-of-authorities-21265.html|title=INDIA Karnataka: New wave of violence and attacks on Christians. Complicity of authorities|last=AsiaNews.it|website=www.asianews.it|access-date=2016-03-22}}</ref>\n\nIncidents of mob attacks against [[Jehovah\u2019s Witnesses]]<ref name=\"articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2008-09-15/news/27737748_1_prayer-halls-bajrang-dal-jayapura-in-chikmagalur-district|title=Bajrang Dal cadre attacks churches in Karnataka|website=timesofindia-economictimes|access-date=2016-03-06}}</ref> have been reported with increasing frequency in Karnataka. The attackers gather in gangs of 20 to 50 individuals to intimidate small groups of Witnesses engaging in the Christian ministry that they are well known for.\n\nA church in [[Mangalore]] was attacked and Doors and window panes were damaged in February 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/mangalore-church-vandalised-modi-call-religious-tolerance/1/420837.html|title=Mangalore church vandalised days after Modi's call for tolerance|website=India Today}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/others-news/mangalore-church-attacked-days-after-pms-remarks-on-religious-tolerance-742220|title=Mangalore Church Attacked Days After PM's Remarks on Religious Tolerance|website=ndtv.com}}</ref> On March 2020, Members of the RSS raided a Christian hospital and attacked two Christian workers during a quarrel which started when a bible was found in one of the treatment rooms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theblaze.com/news/hindu-extremists-attack-christian-hospital-in-india-over-bible-in-room-persecution-watchdog-says|title=Hindu extremists attack Christian hospital in India over Bible in room, persecution watchdog says|date=2020-03-18|website=TheBlaze|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\n===Orissa===\n{{Main|Religious violence in Orissa}}\nIn a well-publicised case, [[Graham Staines]], an Australian Christian missionary, was burnt to death along with his sons Timothy (aged 10) and Philip (aged 6), while they were sleeping in his station wagon at Manoharpur village in [[Keonjhar district]] in [[Orissa, India|Orissa]] in January 1999. He was running the [[Evangelical Missionary Society of Mayurbhanj]], an Australian missionary society.<ref name=\"HRW\"/> In 2003, [[Dara Singh (murderer)|Dara Singh]] was sentenced to life in prison after being convicted of leading the gang responsible.<ref name=frontline>[http://www.frontline.in/static/html/fl2021/stories/20031024003902400.htm The Staines case verdict] V. Venkatesan, Frontline Magazine,  11\u201323 Oct 2003</ref>\n\nOn September 2, 1999, a Catholic Priest was shot by a bow and beaten up to death by fifteen people allegedly religious fundamentalists who later burned down the entire church in [[Keonjhar district]].<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nAn outbreak of violence started on 24 December 2007 at Bamunigam village of [[Kandhamal District]] when local activists forcefully removed a Christmas decoration placed on a site traditionally used during [[Durga Puja]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tehelka.com/story_main37.asp?filename=Ne190108next_stop.asp |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120715034654/http://tehelka.com/story_main37.asp?filename=Ne190108next_stop.asp |url-status=dead |archive-date=15 July 2012 |publisher=Tehalka |title=Tehelka:: Free. Fair. Fearless:Next Stop Orissa |accessdate=8 September 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url= http://ncm.nic.in/pdf/orissa%20report.pdf | title= Report of the NCM visit to Orissa, 6\u20138 January 2008 |publisher=NCM |accessdate = 26 August 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2008, [[Swami Lakshmanananda]], a Hindu swami and VHP anti-conversion and reconversion activist, was attacked and killed, along with four associates by Maoist guerrillas.<ref>[http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/maoists-killed-lakshmanananda-say-orissa-police/article1358482.ece?ref=relatedNews Maoists killed Lakshmanananda, say Orissa Police], The Hindu, 17 October 2008.</ref> The violence that followed resulted in the death of some Christians. The violence later spread to more than 600 villages in 14 of the 30 districts in the state, resulting in 5,600 Christian houses burnt and 54,000 homeless. 38 Christian people were murdered, while 18,000 were injured. Human rights groups estimated 100 deaths, including women, disabled and children. 295 churches and places of worship were destroyed, along with 13 schools and colleges and 5 non-profit organisation offices.<ref>{{cite book |last=Osuri |first=Goldie |title=Religious Freedom in India: Sovereignty and (anti) Conversion |publisher=Routledge |year=2013 |isbn=978-0415665575 |p=39\u201340}}</ref>   As of 2015, the Christian victims were still awaiting justice and rehabilitation.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Editorial |title=Indulging the Hate-mongers |journal=[[Economic and Political Weekly]] |volume=XLIX |number=35 |date=30 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, 1999 a mob of 5,000 locals attacked Ranalai (PIN - 761 017) in Gajapati District and [[arson|set houses on fire]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.tehelka.com/story_main40.asp?filename=Ne130908HindutvasViolentHistory.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-02-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221170851/http://archive.tehelka.com/story_main40.asp?filename=Ne130908HindutvasViolentHistory.asp |archivedate=21 February 2014 }} Tehelka magazine Vol 5, Issue 36, Dated Sept 13, 2008</ref><ref>Volume 16 - Issue 8, Apr. 10 - 23, 1999, India's National Magazine from the publishers of THE HINDU</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.frontline.in/static/html/fl1608/16080360.htm|title=Another attack in Orissa|website=www.frontline.in}}</ref> and engaged in [[looting]]. Three people were injured. The [[Chief Minister (India)|CM]] of Odisha, Sri [[Giridhar Gamang]], visited the next day.\n\nDuring the [[Kandhamal riots]] of 2008, some small [[village]]s in rural areas were targeted by [[extremist]]s. They killed the [[pastor]] of Mukundapur, a small village in Gajapati District<ref>The Hindu, Aug 27, 2008</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/Violence-spreads-in-Orissa/article15290222.ece|title=Violence spreads in Orissa|date=27 August 2008|publisher=|via=www.thehindu.com|newspaper=The Hindu}}</ref>\n\nOn February 2019, A man was [[Decapitation|beheaded]] for leaving Hinduism and converting to Christianity in [[Nabarangpur district]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sabrangindia.in/article/man-beheaded-odisha-converting-christianity|title=Man beheaded in Odisha for converting to Christianity|date=2019-02-25|website=SabrangIndia|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n\n=== Telangana ===\nOn January 2016, around 40 Hindu nationalists beat up a pastor and his congregation members after they falsely accused him of conversion in the [[Nizamabad district|Nizamabad District]]. The attackers tore the pastor's clothes and tore and trampled on the bibles. According to locals, six people were hospitalised and a four-year-old girl's leg was broken.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/telangana/2016/mar/20/Telangana-Unknown-Miscreants-Burn-Down-Makeshift-Chapel-in-Nizamabad-913949.html|title=Telangana: Unknown Miscreants Burn Down Makeshift Chapel in Nizamabad|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\nOn March 2016, a make shift Chapel was burnt down by unknown attackers in Gopanpally, Nizamabad.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nOn October 2019, a fact-finding team consisting of several rights organisation reported 32 instances of attacks on Dalit Christians in the [[Yadadri Bhuvanagiri district]] for the past one year. The attacks included  churches being vandalised and attacks on pastors and their families by activists of the VHP, RSS and ABVP.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/communal-attacks-dalit-christians-rise-telanganas-yadadri-allege-activists-110748|title=Communal attacks on Dalit Christians on the rise in Telangana's Yadadri, allege activists|last=|first=|date=|website=www.thenewsminute.com|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> The activists reported that despite the attacks the police have not taken any action.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/telangana/2019/oct/18/attacks-on-dalit-christians-on-the-rise-in-yadadri-district-allege-rights-activists-2049307.html|title=Attacks on Dalit Christians on the rise in Yadadri district, allege rights activists|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 October 2019, A mob of around 20 people chanting 'Jai Sree Ram' allegedly broke into a pastor's house when the family was celebrating their daughter's birthday party and attacked the pastor and abused his wife in Vasala Marri.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Andhra Pradesh ===\nIn April 1998, a Baptist church in the [[Kurnool district]] was destroyed by VHP militants.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nOn June 23, 2000, Crosses at 40 graves in a cemetery were desecrated in [[Rajahmundry]] and after four days another cemetery was vandalised in [[Vanasthalipuram]] allegedly by religious fundamentalists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rediff.com/%0D%0Anews/2000/jun/23grave1.htm|title=Christian cemetery desecrated in Andhra|last=|first=|date=|website=www.rediff.com|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rediff.com/news/2000/jun/27grave.htm|title=rediff.com: Another Christian cemetery vandalised in AP|website=www.rediff.com|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> On July 2000, three alleged Hindu Nationalists killed a priest in [[Guntur]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/857722.stm|title=BBC News {{!}} SOUTH ASIA {{!}} Priest killed in India|website=news.bbc.co.uk|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n=== Maharashtra ===\nOn February 1998, RSS activists Ransacked a Hospital in [[Latur]] run by the Indian Catholic Association.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.refworld.org/docid/3ae6a84b4.html|title=Refworld {{!}} Politics by Other Means: Attacks Against Christians in India|last=Refugees|first=United Nations High Commissioner for|website=Refworld|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> On October 1998, a prayer hall and  a prayer house in Nasik was attacked and destroyed.<ref name=\":9\" /> On December 25, 1998, armed Bajrang Dal militants accosted about 1,000 attendees of a dance function at a Christian school in [[Borivali]].<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nOn June 1999, the [[Shiv Sena]] launched a series of attacks against Christian kindergarten schools, because the schools were allegedly not giving admission to the Children of the Shiv Sena activists. On June 26, attackers suspected to be Shiv Sena members attacked and vandalised the Sacred Heart school in [[Worli]].<ref name=\":9\" /><ref name=\":12\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=The politics behind anti Christian violence : a compilation of investigation committee reports into acts of violence against the Christian minorities|date=2006|publisher=Media House|others=Puniyani, Ram.|year=|isbn=81-7495-237-3|location=Delhi|pages=367\u2013381|oclc=182969294}}</ref>\n\nOn April 1999, Unknown attackers destroyed a cross at a school run by nuns in [[Yavatmal]].<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rediff.com/news/2000/jun/27chur.htm|title=rediff.com: Church in Maharashtra town ransacked|website=www.rediff.com|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> On June 2000, a catholic church in [[Pusad]] was attacked and ransacked allegedly by fundamentalists.<ref name=\":7\" /> On March 2004, 6 Bajrang Dal militants were arrested for disrupting a private prayer meeting in [[Kopar Khairane]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mumbai/Six-held-for-disrupting-prayer-meeting/articleshow/555231.cms|title=Six held for disrupting prayer meeting - Times of India|website=The Times of India|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nOn March 2015, St. George church in [[Mumbai]] was attacked by masked persons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firstpost.com/mumbai/miscreants-attack-church-navi-mumbai-caught-cctv-footage-2166903.html|title=Masked men attack St George Catholic Church in Navi Mumbai, caught on CCTV footage - Firstpost|website=www.firstpost.com}}</ref> Four people were arrested by the police including a person who operated an illegal gambling den. The police claimed that it was a revenge attack because the accused suspected that a complaint from St. George's Church had led to a police raid on their gambling den.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/mumbai/navi-mumbai-church-attacked-after-raid-on-gambling-den/article1-1330443.aspx|title=Navi Mumbai church attacked after raid on gambling den|date=25 March 2015|website=hindustantimes.com}}</ref>\n\n15 members allegedly belonging to the Bharatiya Janata Party armed with swords, iron rods, knives and empty beer bottles attacked and threw stones at around 40 people offering prayers in a church at [[Kolhapur district]] on December 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/christian-gathering-attacked-during-sunday-prayers-in-maharashtra-oppn-blames-bjp-1417218-2018-12-25|title=Christian gathering attacked during Sunday prayers in Maharashtra, Oppn blames BJP|last=MumbaiDecember 25|first=Kamlesh Damodar Sutar Saurabh Vaktania|last2=December 26|first2=2018UPDATED|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18|last3=Ist|first3=2018 13:20}}</ref> Twelve people were injured and four people were hospitalised.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/cities/christian-gathering-attacked-during-sunday-prayers-in-maharashtra-village-1967913|title=Christian Gathering Attacked During Sunday Prayers In Maharashtra Village|website=NDTV.com|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n\n===Gujarat===\n{{See also|1998 attacks on Christians in southeastern Gujarat}}\nIn Gujarat, 22 churches were burnt or destroyed, and another 16 damaged in the year 1997 alone.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sscnet.ucla.edu/southasia/History/Current_Affairs/Current_affairs.html|title=Anti-Christian Violence in India}}</ref><ref name=\":12\" /> Recently, there has been a sharp increase in violent attacks on Christians.\nA Hindu group claims to have converted 2,000 tribal Christians to Hinduism. The attackers had vandalised places of worship and thus caused strike terror among the tribals. On 18 September, the Central Government issued an advisory under Article 355 of the constitution to the Orissa government along with Karnataka.<ref name=\"Christian Today\">{{cite web|title=Hindu extremists convert 2,000 Christians in India|url=http://www.christiantoday.com/article/hindu.extremists.convert.2000.christians.in.india/15965.htm}}</ref>{{unreliable source?|date=April 2015}}\n\nDuring [[1998 attacks on Christians in southeastern Gujarat]], the Human Rights Watch reported more than 20 incidents of Churches, prayer halls being burnt down and damaged in and around the Dang District. The organisation also reported assaults against Christians, damages and burning down of Churches and Christian institutions in at least 25 villages all over Gujarat from December 25, 1998 to the next ten days.<ref name=\":10\" />\n\nOn November 1997, Alleged VHP militants snatched the mic and shouted pro Hindu slogans during a prayer meeting at Lal Bahadur Shastri Stadium. They also cut the cables and damaged a van.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.indowindow.com/sad/article.php?child=27&article=23|title=Hindutva attacks against the Christian minority in India|website=www.indowindow.com|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nOn March 2, 1998,  Members from VHP, Bajrang Dal and [[Durga Vahini]] beat up a Christian group which included foreign tourists distributing pamphlets for a prayer meeting on march 4th in the Baroda polo ground in Padra. They also made them chant the names of Hindu gods.<ref name=\":8\" /> Later, during the meeting at the Baroda polo ground on March 4, around 300 VHP, Bajrang Dal militants ran amongst the audience creating panic and chaos by bursting fire crackers and blowing whistles. The assailants then went on to mercilessly beat up the audience, set ablaze a car and destroyed the musical instruments. They prevented the buses from taking off and the stranded people were again beaten up. Some people received severe head injuries including fractured hands. Earlier they even tried to set the stage on fire during its construction.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\nOn April 1998, A Jacobite run school was vandalised and a Mary statue in the school was damaged on the pretext that Sanskrit was not taught there.<ref name=\":8\" /> On July 1998, alleged VHP militants dug out a Methodist Christian from a cemetery and dumped the body near a [[Methodist church]] in Kapadvanj.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\nOn August 2000, a Priest was beaten up and made to walk naked through the town after he was reported to be distributing religious pamphlets in [[Surendranagar Dudhrej|Surendranagar]].<ref name=\":5\" /> On March 2002, a Christian Mission was ransacked and burned in [[Sanjeli]] by members of the RSS and VHP.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n=== Chhattisgarh ===\nThe Indian Organization Persecution relief reported that there were 54 instances of attacks in 2016 when BJP was in power in Chattigarh and the number reduced to 21 when Congress took over the state in 2019.<ref name=\":0\" /> Chhattisgarh Christian Association president Arun Pannalal said  93 organised attacks on Christians were reported in the state between 2014 and 2015.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nOn June 2015, A Nun was allegedly tied and sexually assaulted in a hospital in Raipur.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Dahat|first=Pavan|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/nun-assaulted-in-raipur-hospital/article7337688.ece|title=Nun assaulted in Raipur hospital|date=2015-06-21|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-21|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\nOn March 6, 2016, a group of more than 15-20 members of the militant organisation [[Bajrang Dal]] chanting \"Jai Shri Ram\" with saffron bands on their foreheads vandalised a church and attacked the people during the Sunday prayers in [[Raipur district]]. The members destroyed the chairs, fans and attacked the worshipers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-chhattisgarh-church-in-raipur-vandalized-by-mob-chanting-jai-sri-ram-2186136|title=Chhattisgarh: Church in Raipur vandalized by alleged Bajrang Dal mob, 5 injured|date=2016-03-06|website=DNA India|language=en|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> They attacked the women,ripped off their clothes and molested them. Bibles and the pictures hung on the walls were also desecrated and they also thrashed the infants.<ref>{{Cite news|last=ANI|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ani/raipur-church-attack-seven-people-surrender-before-police-116031600198_1.html|title=Raipur church attack: Seven people surrender before police|date=2016-03-16|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\nOn April 2016, Bajrang Dal militants thrashed a pastor,his 7-month pregnant wife and his children in [[Tokopal]]. The attackers kept a sword to the pastor's neck and forced him to say \"Jai Shree Ram\" and when he refused, the members poured petrol on the family and tried to set them ablaze. They also set fire to the church before escaping.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecitizen.in/index.php/en/NewsDetail/index/2/7533/A-7-month-Pregnant-Christian-Woman-Drenched-With-Petrol-by-Bajrang-Dal-Silence-of-the-Lambs|title=A 7-month Pregnant Christian Woman Drenched With Petrol by Bajrang Dal: Silence of the Lambs|last=chaudhary|first=shubhda|website=The Citizen|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> They allegedly destroyed the electronics and set the furniture and scriptures ablaze. The family managed to escape as the church burned.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/raipur/Pastor-pregnant-wife-assaulted-in-Chgarh/articleshow/51888310.cms|title=Pastor, pregnant wife assaulted in Chhattisgarh {{!}} Raipur News - Times of India|last=Apr 19|first=Rashmi Drolia {{!}} TNN {{!}} Updated|last2=2016|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-03-17|last3=Ist|first3=19:19}}</ref>\n\n=== Bihar ===\nIn the [[Gumla district]] two Catholic priests were killed and their skulls crushed on 1996. In October 1997, a decapitated, tortured cigarette-burnt body body of a catholic priest was found in the forests near Hazaribagh allegedly killed by Hindu nationalist groups.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/reports/1999/indiachr/christians8-03.htm#P152_24603|title=III. THE CONTEXT OF ANTI-CHRISTIAN VIOLENCE|last=|first=|date=|website=Human Rights Watch|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn September 20, 1999, at [[Jalalpur, Bihar|Jalalpur]], a nun from Tamil Nadu was stripped,molested and forced to drink the urine of the attackers who also asked her why they have not fled, despite the violence against Christians all over the country.<ref name=\":11\" />\n\nOn May 2001, Several bombs were set off by Hindu nationalists in a Catholic Cathedral in [[Muzaffarpur]]. The attackers left a note which indicated their concern when large number of tribals were embracing Christianity in [[Patna district]]. The note also stated that India is a Hindu Rashtra and Christians must leave India.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n=== Jharkhand ===\nOn April 2019, a mob alleged to be a Hindu vigilante group armed with iron rods and sticks attacked four tribal Christian men who were accused of skinning a dead ox in. One man was killed and the other three were injured. Later investigation revealed the ox died naturally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/world/2019/04/479303/christian-man-beaten-death-latest-cow-lynching-india|title=Christian man beaten to death in latest 'cow lynching' in India|last=AFP|date=2019-04-14|website=NST Online|language=en|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\nOn September 2019, a group of 15-20 men attacked three tribal Christian men for allegedly selling beef after the news spread through WhatsApp messages in [[Khunti district]]. One was killed and the other two were left critical in the attack.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theprint.in/india/mob-lynching-in-jharkhand-again-beaten-up-for-selling-beef-tribal-man-dead-2-critical/295283/|title=Mob lynching in Jharkhand again: Beaten up for 'selling beef', tribal man dead, 2 critical|last=Das|first=Madhuparna|date=2019-09-23|website=ThePrint|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n=== Rajasthan ===\nOn November 1997, VHP militants attacked Christian houses and threatened to leave the district within the next 3 years in [[Banswara district]].<ref name=\":8\" /> On January 2001, the All Indian Christian Council alleged that  of the Bajrang Dal militants attacked two priests and their followers and ransacked the house of one of the priest.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n=== Uttarakhand ===\nA mob razed a church building and attacked the worshippers and their children in [[Khatima]] on 1992.<ref name=\":8\" /> On September 1998, members of the Bajrang Dal, Rana Tharu Parishad and [[Hindu Jagran Manch]] barged into a church and carried out prayers for two hours by placing an idol of Shiva inside the Union Church in Amaun, Udham Singh Nagar district.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\n=== Punjab ===\nOn 31 March 1998, A group of youth ransacked a congregation in Jalandhar. They damaged the lights and chairs and set the stage on fire which made more than a 100 people in the congregation flee in panic. The District BJP president justified the attacks and accused the preachers of trying to convert the people.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=Chandigarh edition|date=April 2, 1998|work=The Indian Express|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Haryana ===\nDuring the time of Easter in 2000, a series of attacks took place against Christian institutions in the towns of [[Karnal]], [[Sonipat]] and [[Panipat]]. On April 22, 2000, three nuns on their way to an Easter mass at [[Rewari]] were attacked and injured by suspected Hindutva group.<ref name=\":13\" />\n\nOn March 2015, a group vandalized a church under construction and replaced with its cross with a Hanuman idol and a flag of [[Rama]] in [[Haryana]]. It also alleged that the group, threatened the priest of murder and stole some a cooler and other items.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/north/story/church-vandalised-haryana-cross-hanuman-idol-244407-2015-03-15|title=Church vandalised in Haryana, cross replaced with Hanuman idol|last=March 15|first=IndiaToday in|last2=March 21|first2=2015UPDATED:|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03|last3=Ist|first3=2015 22:05}}</ref>\n\n=== West Bengal ===\n\nIn March 2015, a 71-year-old [[nun]] was gang raped in [[West Bengal]] during an attack on a convent school in which the school's chapel was ransacked and sacred items stolen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Nun-gang-raped-in-West-Bengal-Cops-detain-eight-people-for-interrogation/articleshow/46571061.cms|title=Nun gang-raped in West Bengal: Cops detain eight people for interrogation - Times of India \u25ba|website=indiatimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/03/14/india-nun-gang-rape_n_6869266.html | title=HuffPost is now a part of Verizon Media}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/cities/kolkata/archbishop-clears-mamata-blames-modi-govt-for-rising-violence-against-minorities/|title=Nun Gang Rape Case: Archbishop clears Mamata, blames Modi govt for rising violence against minorities|date=17 March 2015|website=indianexpress.com}}</ref> The Police identified all eight perpetrators and arrested six of them, two of whom were Bangladeshi nationals.<ref>[http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-ranaghat-gang-rape-case-police-detains-two-bangladesh-nationals-2070557 Ranaghat gang-rape case: Police detains two Bangladesh nationals], DNA India, 20 March 2015.</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-india-32143051 Indian nun rape case: Police make more arrests], BBC News, 1 April 2015.</ref><ref>[http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2015/04/suspects-nun-rape-case-indian-court-150403194634975.html Suspects in nun rape case appear in Indian court], Al Jazeera News, 3 April 2015.</ref>\n\nOn December 2019, members belonging to the RSS and BJP hurled [[bomb]]s at a church chanting \"[[Jai Shri Ram]]\" in the [[East Midnapore district]] during the Christmas celebrations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/3-held-for-attack-on-bengal-church/story-cg7rz0jOupuPnBi01tcuFI.html|title=3 held for attack on Bengal church|date=2020-12-30|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> The members attacked the people as they fled in panic and went on to desecrate the entire church. The members destroyed the furniture, ceiling fans, sound systems, window panes, microphones,the pastor's car and even the water tank.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.india.com/news/india/3-arrested-for-bomb-blast-vandalism-at-west-bengal-church-3893838/|title=3 Arrested For Bomb Blast, Vandalism at West Bengal Church|last=Desk|first=India com News|date=2019-12-30|website=India News, Breaking News, Entertainment News {{!}} India.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> Four persons, including two children, were injured in the attack.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/3-arrested-for-throwing-bombs-at-bengal-church-vandalising-property-2156211|title=3 Arrested For Throwing Bombs At Bengal Church, Vandalising Property|website=NDTV.com|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>{{Persecutions of the Catholic Church sidebar}}\n\n==Response==\n===US State Department===\nIn its annual human rights reports for 1999, the [[United States Department of State]] criticised India for \"increasing societal violence against Christians.\"<ref name=\"Expressindia\">{{cite web|title=US rights report slams India for anti-Christian violence|url=http://www.expressindia.com/news/ie/daily/19990227/ige27064.html|date=27 February 1999|accessdate=17 December 2007}}</ref> The report on anti-Christian violence listed over 90 incidents of anti-Christian violence, ranging from damage of religious property to violence against Christians pilgrims. The incidents listed in the report were attributed to local media reports and information gathered by Christian groups in India.<ref name=\"Expressindia\"/>\n\n===National Commission for Minorities===\nAfter the [[2008 attacks on Christians in southern Karnataka]] by [[Bajrang Dal]] and [[Sri Ram Sena]] activists, the [[National Commission for Minorities]] accused the Karnataka government of serious lapses in handling the situation. They were found directly responsible for allowing the violence to spread, and claimed the police failed to solve the issue effectively as the violence continues. They also clarified that there were no reported complaints of forced conversion registered in the state.<ref name=\"ptinews.com\"/><ref name=\"mangalorean.com\"/>\n\n===National Integration Council of India===\nOn 13 October 2008, the [[National Integration Council]] of India called a special meeting chaired by [[Manmohan Singh]], then Prime Minister of India, where he condemned the violence  of Hindu militant organisations such as Bajrang Dal, VHP etc.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}} The prime minister had earlier publicly admitted that the ongoing violence against the Christian communities was a matter of great \"national shame\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/Editorial/India_under_siege_/articleshow/3610403.cms |title=India under siege |publisher=Economictimes.indiatimes.com |date=18 October 2008 |accessdate=29 April 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Vatican===\nOn 12 October 2008, [[Pope Benedict XVI]] criticised the continuing anti-Christian violence in India.\n\nOn 28 October, the [[Holy See|Vatican]] called upon the memory of [[Mahatma Gandhi]] for an end to the religious violence in Orissa. In a written address to Hindus, the Vatican office said Christian and Hindu leaders needed to foster a belief in [[non-violence]] among followers.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://in.reuters.com/article/topNews/idINIndia-36186520081028 |title=Vatican invokes Gandhi in plea to end Orissa violence |publisher=In.reuters.com |date=28 October 2008 |accessdate=29 April 2010}}</ref> Although the Mahatma had been strong in his opposition to forced conversion and Christian missionary activities, he had denounced violence as an appropriate response.<ref>Conversion: Old Worlds and New, p. 273,  Kenneth Mills, Anthony Grafton, University Rochester Press, quote= \"Furthermore, Gandhi's famous distrust of Christian missionaries and Christian conversions offered a screen.\"</ref><ref>Gandhi's Pilgrimage of Faith: From Darkness to Light, Uma Majmudar, p.119, Suny Press, quote=\"Gandhi also disapproved of schools run by the Christian Missionaries because of their Western bias.\"</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india/his-faith-our-faith/story-sdpOimN69y2gTuSJs1SltI.html |title=His faith, our faith |publisher=Hindustan Times |date=29 January 2008 |accessdate=29 April 2010|quote=From these two beliefs followed the third, which was that Gandhi rejected conversion and missionary work.}}</ref><ref>http://www.mkgandhi.org/ebks/gandhiji-on-religious-conversion.pdf</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Religious violence in India]]\n* [[Violence against Muslims in India]]\n* [[Religion in India]]\n* [[Persecution of Christians]]\n* [[Persecution of Hindus]]\n* [[Communalism (South Asia)]]\n* [[Hindutva]]\n* [[Saffron terror]]\n* [[Christian terrorism]]\n* [[1998 attacks on Christians in southeastern Gujarat]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Bauman |first=Chad M. |title=Hindu-Christian Conflict in India: Globalization, Conversion and the Coterminal Castes and Tribes |journal=The Journal of Asian Studies |volume=72 |pages=633\u2013653 |number=3 |date=August 2013 |url=http://digitalcommons.butler.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1271&context=facsch_papers |doi=10.1017/s0021911813000569}}\n* {{cite book |last=Osuri |first=Goldie |title=Religious Freedom in India: Sovereignty and (anti) Conversion |publisher=Routledge |year=2013 |isbn=978-0415665575}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Uma |first1=Saumya |last2=Grover |first2=Vrinda |title=Kandhamal: The Law must Change its Course |publisher=MARG: Multiple Action Research Group |location=New Delhi |year=2010 | isbn= 978-81-87377-19-1 |url=http://works.bepress.com/saumyauma/31/}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Asia in topic|Violence against Christians in}}\n\n[[Category:Christianity in India]]\n[[Category:Religiously motivated violence in India]]\n[[Category:Anti-Christian sentiment in Asia]]\n[[Category:Violence against Christians]]\n[[Category:Violence against Christians in India| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Anti-Christian violence in India}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n[[File:Adoration Mangalore.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Destroyed property inside Adoration Monastery, [[Mangalore]], after it was vandalised by activists belonging to the [[Bajrang Dal]], during the [[September 2008 attacks on Christians in Mangalore]]]]\n'''Anti-Christian violence in India''' is [[Religious violence|religiously-motivated violence]] against [[Christians]] in India.<ref name=\"HRW\" /> Violence against Christians has been seen by the organisation [[Human Rights Watch]] as a tactic used to meet political ends.<ref name=\"HRW\" /> The acts of violence include [[arson]] of [[Church (building)|churches]], [[Forced conversion|conversion of Christians by force]] and threats of physical violence, sexual assaults, murder of Christian priests and destruction of Christian schools, colleges, and cemeteries.<ref name=\"MANAS\">{{cite web|title=Anti-Christian Violence in India|url=http://www.sscnet.ucla.edu/southasia/History/Current_Affairs/Current_affairs.html|author=Vinay Lal|work=Manas: India and Its Neighbors|publisher=UCLA College of Letters and Science}}</ref><ref name=\"HRW\">{{cite web|title=Anti-Christian Violence on the Rise in India|url=http://hrw.org/english/docs/1999/09/30/india1626.htm|publisher=[[Human Rights Watch]]|date=29 September 1999 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090211152613/https://www.hrw.org/legacy/english/docs/1999/09/30/india1626.htm |archive-date=February 11, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2017, the [[United States Commission on International Religious Freedom|US Commission on International Religious Freedom]] (USCIRF) ranked India\u2019s persecution severity at \u201cTier 2\u201d along with [[Christianity in Iraq|Iraq]] and [[Christianity in Afghanistan|Afghanistan]].<ref name=chrtoday>{{cite web|last=Zylstra|first=Sarah Erkhoff|url=http://www.christianitytoday.com/news/2017/august/state-department-international-religious-freedom-report-irf.html |title=State Department's Unusually Short Religious Freedom Update: ISIS Is Bad|publisher=Christianity Today|date=August 2017|accessdate=August 28, 2017}}</ref> Over the past seven years, India has risen from No. 31 to No. 10 on [[Open Doors|Open Doors']] World Watch List, ranking just behind [[Christianity in Iran|Iran]] in persecution severity.<ref name=opendoors>{{cite web| url=https://www.opendoorsusa.org/christian-persecution/world-watch-list/india | title=World Watch List - India|date=|accessdate=January 31, 2018}}</ref><ref name=persupdate>{{cite web|last=Kaur|first=Surinder|url=http://www.persecution.in/node/4372|title=Police in Indian State of Uttar Pradesh Threaten and Extort Christian Families|publisher=Christian Persecution Update|date=July 4, 2017|accessdate=August 29, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170830235615/http://www.persecution.in/node/4372|archive-date=30 August 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2019, [[USCIRF]] repeatedly placed India as Tier-2 in minority persecution.<ref>https://www.uscirf.gov/sites/default/files/Tier2_INDIA_2019.pdf</ref>\n\n==Background==\nFrom 1964 to 1996, at least 38 incidents of violence against Christians were reported. In 1997, 24 such incidents were reported. Since 1998, Christians in India have faced a wave of violence.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news|title= Pope Lands in India Amid Rise in Anti-Christian Violence|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9807E4DA163AF935A35752C1A96F958260 | work=The New York Times | first=Alessandra | last=Stanley | date=6 November 1999 | accessdate=1 April 2010}}</ref> In 1998 alone, 90 incidents were reported.<ref name=\"MANAS\"/>\n\nA November 2001 survey by the [[National Commission for Minorities]](NCM) reported 27 attacks on Christian institutions and Christians in 1997, 86 instances in 1998, 120 instances in 1999 and 216 attacks in 2000. According to the NCM, the \"persecution\" of Christians had increased since the Bharatiya Janata Party came to power in 1998.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nIn 1999 a [[Human Rights Watch]] (HRW) report stated that [[Vishva Hindu Parishad]] (VHP), [[Bajrang Dal]], and [[Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh]] (the sister organisations of the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]]) are the most accused  organisations for violence against Christians in India.<ref name=\"HRW\" /> The [[National Commission for Minorities]] has alleged that the State governments ruled by the Bharatiya Janata Party and its allies provided support to the perpetrators.<ref name=\"ptinews.com\">{{cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/NCM-blames-Bajrang-Dal-for-Karnataka-Orissa-violence/articleshow/3509247.cms |title=NCM blames Bajrang Dal for Karnataka, Orissa violence |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=September 21, 2008 |publisher=[[The Times of India]] |access-date=July 30, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"mangalorean.com\">{{cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-karnataka/no-case-of-forcible-conversion-in-udupi-district-qureshi/article1340238.ece |title=No case of forcible conversion in Udupi district: Qureshi |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=September 18, 2008 |newspaper=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=July 30, 2018}}</ref> In 2001, the [[All India Christian Council]] reported that an attack against Indian Christians occurs every 36 hours.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nIn most reported cases the named perpetrators are members of the ''[[Sangh Parivar]]'' organisations. The ''Sangh Parivar'' are small subgroups that formed under the umbrella of the ''[[Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh]]'' (RSS), an umbrella organisation whose roots date back to 1925. The RSS, who promote a form of [[nationalism]], oppose the spread of \"foreign religions\" like [[Islam]] and [[Christianity]].<ref name=bauman>{{Cite book| publisher = Oxford University Press| isbn = 978-0-19-026631-8| last = Bauman| first = Chad M.| title = Pentecostals, Proselytization, and Anti-Christian Violence in Contemporary India| date = 2015-02-02 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DoFxBgAAQBAJ&pg=PT14}}</ref>  According to Human Rights Watch,  ''Sangh Parivar'' and local media were also involved in promoting anti-Christian propaganda in [[Gujarat]].<ref name=\"HRW\"/>  Mainstream [[Protestant]], [[Catholic]] and [[Orthodox Christianity|Orthodox]] Christians are targeted far less frequently than [[Evangelical]] and [[Pentecostal]] Christians.<ref name=bauman />\n\nMultiple news organisations reported an increase in incidents of violence against Christians after the new BJP government under [[Narendra Modi]] came to power after the [[2014 Indian general election|general election in April\u2013May 2014]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/politics/violence-against-christians-cong-slams-govt/article7004032.ece|title=Violence against Christians: Cong slams govt|website=thehindubusinessline.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/bearing-the-cross-of-communal-discord/article1-1326535.aspx|title=Bearing the cross: Recent attacks against Christians worrisome|date=15 March 2015|website=hindustantimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oneindia.com/india/churches-under-fire-a-list-of-recent-church-attacks-in-the-country-1685114.html|title=Churches under fire! A list of recent church attacks in the country|website=oneindia.com|date=16 March 2015}}</ref><ref name=indiatimes>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/articleshow/57055700.cms |title=Religious Minorities, Dalits Face Discrimination in India: Report|newspaper= The Economic Times|date=Feb 9, 2017| accessdate=August 29, 2017}}</ref> One investigation of crime records shows that church attack figures under NDA rule match those under UPA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Church-attack-figures-in-UPA-rule-match-those-under-NDA/articleshow/46830877.cms|title=Church attack figures in UPA rule match those under NDA - Times of India \u25ba|website=indiatimes.com}}</ref> In 2014 the Ministry of Home Affairs reported a \u201csteep 30 per cent rise in the number of communal violence incidents in 2013 as compared to 2012, with the maximum number of cases being reported from [[Uttar Pradesh]].\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/communal-incidents-up-by-30-up-tops-list/|title=Communal incidents up by 30%, UP tops list|date=2014-02-06|work=The Indian Express|access-date=2017-09-04|language=en-US}}</ref> Reported incidents of abuse carried out against Christians in India went up to 177 in 2015, and escalated to 300 in 2016, according to the Evangelical Fellowship of India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldea.org/news/4651/evangelical-fellowship-of-india-persecution-report-2015|title=Evangelical Fellowship of India Persecution Report 2015|website=www.worldea.org|language=en|access-date=2017-09-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180910153755/http://www.worldea.org/news/4651/evangelical-fellowship-of-india-persecution-report-2015|archive-date=10 September 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn a report by the Indian organisation Persecution Relief, the crimes against Christians increased by 60% from 2016 to 2019. There were 330 incidents in 2016, 440 incidents in 2017, 477 in 2018 and 527 incidents of hate crimes in 2019. The organisation reported there has been a direct link between [[Bharatiya Janata Party|Baratiya Janata Party]] gaining power in a state and increase in the attacks against Christians in the state.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalheraldindia.com/india/on-narendra-modi-watch-steep-rise-in-crime-against-christians-between-2016-and-2019|title=On Narendra Modi's watch, steep rise in crime against Christians between 2016 and 2019|website=National Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\nThe persecution of Christians in India increased sharply in the year 2016, according to a report by [[Open Doors]].<ref name=\"OpenDoors\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/jan/11/christians-in-india-increasingly-under-attack-study-shows|title=Christians in India increasingly under attack, study shows|first=Harriet|last=Sherwood|date=11 January 2017|website=the Guardian}}</ref> India was ranked 15th in the world in terms of danger to Christians, up from 31st four years earlier. According to the report, it is estimated that a church was burnt down or a cleric beaten on average 10 times a week in India in the year to 31 October 2016, a threefold increase on the previous year.<ref name=\"OpenDoors\" /> According to the [[All India Christian Council]], there was an attack on Christians recorded every 40 hours in India in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christianpost.com/news/violent-persecution-christians-india-attack-every-40-hours-report-182039/|title=Violent Persecution of Christians Rises in India, 'An Attack Being Recorded Every 40 Hours': Report|website=christianpost.com}}</ref> There were 26 documented cases of violence against Christians in the country between January and March 2016, while the central government refrained from speaking out against it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2016/03/14/christian-persecution-by-hindus-rises-in-india-say-humanitarian-groups.html|title=Christian persecution by Hindus rises in India, say humanitarian groups|first=Perry|last=Chiaramonte|date=14 March 2016|website=foxnews.com}}</ref> There were incidents of anti-Christian violence in Uttar Pradesh and Rajasthan around Christmas in December 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cruxnow.com/global-church/2016/12/30/christmas-attacks-confirm-threats-facing-christians-india/|title=Christmas attacks confirm threats facing Christians in India|date=30 December 2016|website=cruxnow.com}}</ref>\n\n==Overview of notable incidents==\n{{Quote box\n| quote = The Narendra Modi-led NDA government should award and provide legal and administrative protection to Hindus who attack churches across the country. Churches are no longer places of worship but factories for conversion of Hindus into Christianity,\n| source = - Munna Kumar Shukla, general secretary of the [[Hindu Mahasabha]] <ref name=\"shuklaquote\" />\n| align = right\n| width = 40em\n| bgcolor = #ffd2c7\n}}\nAccording to the [[BBC]], even though the [[National Commission for Minorities|National Commission for minorities]] and the [[Ministry of Home Affairs (India)|Ministry of Home Affairs]] report hundreds of cases of attacks against Christians per year, the number is certainly higher as Indian Journalists estimate that only 10% of the incidents are ever recorded.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Haynes, Jeffrey.|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/721900527|title=Religion, politics and international relations : selected essays|date=2011|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=|location=Abingdon, Oxon|pages=150|oclc=}}</ref>\n\nThe general secretary of the [[Hindu Mahasabha]], Munna Kumar Shukla, said that it is not illegal to attack a church and it violates no law and also said the organisation would award those who attack churches.<ref name=\"shuklaquote\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/church-attacks-not-illegal-hindu-outfit/article7127261.ece|title=Church attacks not illegal: Hindu outfit|date=2015-04-22|work=The Hindu|access-date=|url-status=live|language=|issn=|}}</ref>\n\n=== Uttar Pradesh ===\nThe small Christian minority of 0.18% in the state of [[Uttar Pradesh]] with a population of 200 million, are the target of increasing violence.<ref name=\":0\" /> Citing an article by Institute for Leadership and Community Development, [[India Today]] lists Uttar Pradesh first among states of India which \u201ctend to have the greatest number of incidents of religiously-motivated attacks and communal violence.\u201d<ref name=indiatoday>{{cite web|last=Borgohain|first=Sonalee| url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/muslims-dalits-religious-attacks-grew-in-india-narendra-modi-us-report/1/879370.html |title=Attacks Against Muslims, Dalits Grew Sharply in India Under Modi: US Report|publisher=India Today|date=February 10, 2017| accessdate=August 28, 2017}}</ref> In the first half of 2016, there were more hate crimes against Christians in [[Uttar Pradesh]] than in any other state of India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldwatchmonitor.org/old-site-imgs-pdfs/4628515.pdf|title=Hate and Targeted Violence against Christians in India|last=|first=|date=August 2016|website=Evangelical Fellowship of India|access-date=August 31, 2017}}</ref> In a 2018 annual report, the Indian organisation Persecution Relief recorded 129 attacks against Christians in Uttar Pradesh alone, the highest among all states in India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/how-hindu-extremists-are-shutting-down-christian-churches-why-are-you-1360934|title=How Hindu extremists are shutting down Christian churches: 'Why are you worshipping a foreign god?'|last=Lal|first=Surinder Kaur|last2=EDT|first2=M. Clark On 3/26/19 at 8:33 PM|date=2019-03-26|website=Newsweek|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> The organisation also reported that there has been a direct link in increase in crimes with the rise of [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] in the state. In 2016, there were 39 incidents of hate crimes, but by 2019, the number increased to 109.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n{{Cquote|I will ensure that India is freed of Muslims and Christians by December 31, 2021\n| source = Rajeshwar Singh, Head of Dharm Jagran Samiti UP.<ref name=\":djs2021\"></ref>\n| width = 30%\n| float = right\n}}\n\nOn December 2014, Rajeshwar Singh the head of the state's Dharm Jagran Samiti said:<blockquote>Our target is to make India a Hindu Rashtra by 2021. The Muslims and Christians don't have any right to stay here. So they would either be converted to Hinduism or forced to run away from here.<ref name=\":djs2021\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/dharm-jagran-samiti-leader-vows-to-create-hindu-rashtra-by-2021-231854-2014-12-19|title=Dharm Jagran Samiti leader vows to create Hindu rashtra by 2021|last=LucknowDecember 19|first=Piyush Srivastava|last2=December 19|first2=2014UPDATED|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18|last3=Ist|first3=2014 09:54}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nOn March 1998, Bajrang Dal militants chanting \"Jai Shri Ram\" attacked people with iron rods, burned down the tent, stole all the electronic-musical instruments and kidnapped a young man at a Christian assembly in [[Kanpur]]. Even the police threatened the Christians that they would not return the stolen property if they file an FIR. The ''[[Amar Ujala]]'' reported that the Bajrang Dal members also performed a \"naked dance\" in-front of the gathering.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sabrang.com/cc/comold/april98/sreport.htm|title=Saffron targets People of the Cross|last=|first=|date=April 1998|website=Communalism Combat|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn April 22 2000, a priest and some nuns who were leading a group was surrounded and attacked by Bajrang Dal in [[Mathura]].<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ipsnews.net/2000/04/rights-india-church-called-for-talks-on-easter-attacks/|title=RIGHTS-INDIA: Church Called for Talks on Easter Attacks|last=|first=|date=Apr 27, 2000|website=Inter Press Service|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn August 2 2015, a group of Hindutva fundamentalists disrupted a catholic prayer in [[Ghazipur]] and threatened the attendees to leave the area.<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.refworld.org/docid/57add86ec.html|title=Refworld {{!}} 2015 Report on International Religious Freedom - India|last=UNHCFR|first=|date=|website=Refworld|language=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, Christian families in Uttar Pradesh were beaten and denied water for their crops.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.express.co.uk/news/world/820571/christian-families-beaten-water-india-hindu-extremism-persecution|title=Christian families beaten and left without water in latest horrifying persecution|first=Katie|last=Mansfield|date=24 June 2017|website=express.co.uk}}</ref> On July 2019, members of the militant group [[Bajrang Dal]] allegedly beat up a pastor on suspicion of conversion in [[Kanpur]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsclick.in/rising-attacks-christians|title=Rising Attacks on Christians|date=2019-07-31|website=NewsClick|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> in March 2002, members of the RSS ransacked the Indian Missionary Society in Dhudia and attacked the clergy .<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.refworld.org/docid/3f7d4da823.html|title=Refworld {{!}} India: Treatment of Christians by Hindus, particularly the treatment of Christians who have converted from Hinduism; and the protection available to them|last=Refugees|first=United Nations High Commissioner for|website=Refworld|language=en|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n=== Tamil Nadu ===\nThe annual 2018 report by the Indian Organization Persecution relief has ranked [[Tamil Nadu]] to be the 2nd state after Uttar Pradesh to record highest instances of attacks against Christians. 29 such instances were recorded in 2016, there were 57 instances in 2017 and 2018 recorded 67 incidents. The organisation reported that most of the attacks in the state were committed by [[Hindu Munnani]] members and their allied organisations.<ref name=\":0\" /> On May 2018, The [[Hindu Makkal Katchi]] president Arjun Sampath said that Christians and Muslims are not Tamil people.<ref name=\":arjunsampathquote\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibctamil.com/religion/80/100117?ref=recommended1?ref=fb|title=\u0bae\u0bc1\u0bb8\u0bcd\u0bb2\u0bbf\u0bae\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bc1\u0bae\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bbf\u0bb1\u0bbf\u0bb8\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bb5\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bc1\u0bae\u0bcd \u0ba4\u0bae\u0bbf\u0bb4\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bcd \u0b87\u0bb2\u0bcd\u0bb2\u0bc8\u0baf\u0bbe?|last=David|first=Niraj|date=2018-05-04|website=IBC Tamil|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> \n\n{{Cquote|Christians and Muslims are not Tamil people.\n| source = Arjun Sampath, President of Hindu Makkal Katchi. <ref name=\":arjunsampathquote\"></ref>\n| float = right\n}}\nOn February 1998, the Bethany Fellowship Church was demolished and its participants were brutally attacked in [[Ayyampalayam, Erode]].<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/reports/1999/indiachr/christians8-05.htm|title=V. ATTACKS ACROSS THE COUNTRY|last=|first=|date=|website=Human Rights Watch|access-date=}}</ref> On October 1999, a Syrian Catholic church was set on fire near [[Kanyakumari]].<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sabrangindia.in/indepth/attacks-minorities-unrelenting|title=Attacks on minorities unrelenting|date=1999-11-01|website=SabrangIndia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn October 2008, During the [[2008 attacks on Christians in southern Karnataka]] the police reported 20 graves in a cemetery were desecrated in a district south of chennai, three churches were stoned in the districts of Karur and Erode, bibles in the outer walls of Chennai and Coimbatore were damaged, a statue of Mother Mary was stolen in Krishnagiri, a Virgin Mary icon was damaged in Kanyakumari and an idol of Jesus in Madurai was vandalised.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/latest-headlines/story/4-held-in-tamil-nadu-for-attacking-christian-institutions-31285-2008-10-09|title=4 held in Tamil Nadu for attacking Christian institutions|last=ChennaiOctober 9|first=Indo-Asian News Service|last2=October 9|first2=2008UPDATED|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-03-03|last3=Ist|first3=2008 20:37}}</ref> Four members belonging to the [[Hindu Munnani]] were arrested on October 9th and the number reached 22 on the next day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/latest-headlines/story/22-arrested-in-tamil-nadu-for-desecrating-christian-institutions-31362-2008-10-10|title=22 arrested in Tamil Nadu for desecrating Christian institutions|last=ChennaiOctober 10|first=Indo-Asian News Service|last2=October 10|first2=2008UPDATED|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-03-03|last3=Ist|first3=2008 20:09}}</ref>\n\nMembers of the [[Hindu Makkal Katchi]] vandalised a prayer hall, broke all the glass windows, damaged the furniture and disposed the prayer books in Coimbatore on January 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/coimbatore/Church-authorities-seek-police-protection/articleshow/11547861.cms|title=Church authorities seek police protection {{!}} Coimbatore News - Times of India|last=Jan 19|first=TNN {{!}} Updated|last2=2012|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16|last3=Ist|first3=05:51}}</ref>\n\nOn January 28 2016, A mob of around 35 Hindu nationalists attacked a catholic priest and 3 other church officials in their car in [[Ettimadai]]. They were punched, kicked and attacked with granite stones.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/world/christian-persecution-by-hindus-rises-in-india-say-humanitarian-groups|title=Christian persecution by Hindus rises in India, say humanitarian groups|last=Chiaramonte|first=Perry|date=2016-03-10|website=Fox News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> The mob then dragged them, beat them and made them walk for 2.5 kilometres in a national highway. During the incident the police refused to intervene and stood there idly. All the victims were hospitalised and the priest was left unconscious.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mattersindia.com/2016/02/mob-attacks-priest-catholics-in-coimbatore/|title=Mob attacks priest, Catholics in Coimbatore|date=2016-02-01|website=Matters India|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mattersindia.com/2016/02/bishops-demand-probe-into-coimbatore-mob-attack/|title=Bishops demand probe into Coimbatore mob attack|date=2016-02-01|website=Matters India|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> On March 2016, a mob of Hindu Munnani members vandalised a newly built CSI church in [[Kalapatti]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/coimbatore/Church-attack-Hindu-Munnani-members-protest-against-arrest/articleshow/51433259.cms|title=Church attack: Hindu Munnani members protest against arrest {{!}} Coimbatore News - Times of India|last=Mar 17|first=TNN {{!}} Updated|last2=2016|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24|last3=Ist|first3=01:13}}</ref>\n\nHindu Makkal Katchi's Tirunelveli district president and the secretary locked up a girls school run by catholic nuns because they were supporting the anti-[[National Eligibility cum Entrance Test (Undergraduate)|NEET]] agitations on September 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/hindu-makkal-katchi-men-held-for-locking-up-christian-school-tirunelveli/article19678082.ece|title=Hindu Makkal Katchi men held for locking up Christian school|date=2017-09-13|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-17|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\nAround 25 members allegedly belonging to the [[Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh|RSS]] and [[BJP]] desecrated a prayer hall and attacked the worshippers during the Christmas celebrations on December 2017 in Coimbatore. The pastor suffered a head injury, a woman suffered a fracture and others had minor injuries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/rss-members-allegedly-vandalise-prayer-hall-coimbatore-decked-christmas-72906|title=RSS members allegedly vandalise prayer hall in Coimbatore decked up for Christmas|last=|first=|date=|website=The News Minute|access-date=}}</ref> A local BJP leader and three others were arrested.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/tamil-nadu-news/coimbatore-bjp-leader-arrested-in-attack-on-christian-prayer-hall-cops-1785772|title=Coimbatore BJP Leader Arrested In Attack On Christian Prayer Hall: Cops|website=NDTV.com|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> On May 2017, Hindu Munnani members were alleged of attacking a Church three times in the month in [[Sulur]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/take-action-hindu-munnani-church-attack-christians-threaten-return-ration-cards-61869|title='Take action on Hindu Munnani for Church attack': Christians threaten to return ration cards|last=|first=|date=|website=The News Minute|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nAround 30 members of the [[Hindu Munnani]] ransacked a prayer hall in Madurai on March 11, 2018. They burned bibles, attempted to strip the pastor's wife naked and threatened to kill the pastor's family if they did not close down the prayer hall.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/tamil-nadu-news/3-christian-prayer-halls-vandalised-in-madurai-since-sunday-1823531|title=3 Christian Prayer Halls Vandalised In Madurai Since Sunday|website=NDTV.com|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref> The attackers then went to three other Pentecostal halls and threatened them of attacks if they were not shut in a week.<ref>{{Cite news|last=B.a|first=Pon Vasanth|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Madurai/hindu-right-wing-group-vandalises-prayer-home-madurai/article23041946.ece|title=Hindu right wing group vandalises prayer home|date=2018-03-11|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-08|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/madurai/minority-commissioner-talks-to-pastors/articleshow/63323846.cms|title=Minority commissioner talks to pastors {{!}} Madurai News - Times of India|last=Mar 16|first=TNN {{!}} Updated|last2=2018|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-03-08|last3=Ist|first3=11:15}}</ref>\n\nMembers belonging to the RSS attacked an ex-BJP man who converted to Christianity with a [[sickle]] in Coimbatore on April 2018. The man was hospitalised due to Head and neck injuries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/coimbatore/rss-workers-attack-ex-bjp-man-who-converted-to-christianity/articleshow/63837542.cms|title='RSS workers' attack ex-BJP man who converted to Christianity {{!}} Coimbatore News - Times of India|last=Apr 20|first=TNN {{!}}|last2=2018|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18|last3=Ist|first3=00:51}}</ref>\n\nOn July 2019, residents in the Alagumalai village of Tirupur district accused the Hindu Munnani of creating religious tensions after the outfit built an iron fence on a concrete road to block a way used by mostly Christian dalits.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsclick.in/dalit-residents-discriminated-untouchability-fence-tirupur-district|title=Dalit Residents Discriminated with Untouchability Fence in Tirupur District|date=2019-06-12|website=NewsClick|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> On August 2019, a mob of Hindu Munnani members attacaked a group of 40 christian pilgrims, tore their posters, verbally abused them and accused the pilgrims of preaching Christianity in Velankanni.The local DSP said the pilgrims were not preaching and attackers were fanatics with no motive.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/hindu-munnani-members-held-assaulting-pilgrims-walking-velankanni-church-107603|title=Hindu Munnani members held for assaulting pilgrims walking to Velankanni Church|last=Thirumurthy|first=Priyanka|date=21 August 2019|website=The News Minute|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Delhi===\nOn September 1998, a St. Bernard statue was chopped and thrown out of the campus in [[Jesus and Mary College]],.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nOn December 2014, the [[St. Sebastian's Church (Dilshad Garden)]] was set ablaze by unidentified men which reduced the entire interior to ashes.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Perappadan|first=Bindu Shajan|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Delhi/archbishop-writes-to-pm-wants-judicial-inquiry/article6654061.ece|title=Dilshad garden church attack: Archbishop seeks judicial inquiry|date=2014-12-02|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-21|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> A forensic team reportedly found traces of kerosene. Later, the [[Aam Aadmi Party]] accused the police of ignoring clear evidence of arson.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/delhi-news/protests-after-fire-in-delhi-church-police-investigate-possible-arson-707034|title=Protests After Fire in Delhi Church, Police Investigate Possible Arson|website=ndtv.com}}</ref> On December 2014, unknown assailants threw stones and broke the windows at Our Lady of Fatima Forane Church during the evening mass at South Delhi.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india/two-held-for-vandalising-vikaspuri-church/story-2YY8ivPZxWy7XoEJEQv07M.html|title=Two held for vandalising Vikaspuri church|date=2015-01-15|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\nOn January 2015, Two unidentified men vandalised a church in [[Vikaspuri]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/church-vandalised-in-west-delhis-vikaspuri-area-235729-2015-01-15|title=Church vandalised in West Delhi's Vikaspuri area|last=DelhiJanuary 15|first=Mail Today Bureau New|last2=January 15|first2=2015UPDATED|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-03-21|last3=Ist|first3=2015 05:03}}</ref> On February 2015, Unidentified men broke open the St. Alphonsa church's main gate in Vasant Kunj and ransacked its premises.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/assembly-delhi/church-in-delhi-vandalised-five-days-before-assembly-elections-reports-736306|title=Church in Delhi Allegedly Vandalised 5 Days Before Assembly Elections|website=NDTV.com|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\nOn February 2015, a catholic school was vandalised and the principal's office ransacked in Vasant Vihar. The Archdiocese spokesperson Sankar said that 5 churches have been attacked since December 2014 allegedly by fundamentalist groups to instill fear among the community.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/christian-school-vandalized-in-delhi-442075.html|title=Christian school vandalized in Delhi|date=2015-02-13|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, St. Mary's Church in [[Agra]] was vandalised and statues of [[Mother Mary]] and the [[Infant Jesus]] were damaged.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/church-vandalised-in-agra-mother-mary-s-statues-knocked-over/article1-1337771.aspx|title=Agra church vandalised, Mother Mary idol damaged|date=16 April 2015|website=hindustantimes.com}}</ref> Police arrested a Muslim man who reportedly was angry about being rejected by a Christian girl.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Spurned-lover-attacked-Agra-church-Cops/articleshow/47033360.cms|title=Spurned lover attacked Agra church: Cops - Times of India \u25ba|website=indiatimes.com}}</ref>    \n\nOn May 5, 2018 St. Stephen's college chapel was vandalised. The Chapel's door and the cross outside were desecrated with pro-Hindutva slogans.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/delhi-news/there-should-be-a-temple-here-vandalism-hits-st-stephens-college-chapel-1847663|title=\"There Should Be A Temple Here\": Vandalism Hits St Stephen's College Chapel|website=ndtv.com}}</ref>\n\n===Jammu and Kashmir===\n{{Rquote|right|The anti-Christian intolerance in Jammu and Kashmir is reaching alarming proportions.|Sajan George, The president of the Global Council of Indian Christians (GCIC)<ref name=autogenerated3>{{cite web|last=Gheddo |first=Piero |url=http://www.asianews.it/news-en/Indian-Kashmir,-two-Christians-arrested-on-false-charges-of-forced-conversions-27639.html |title=INDIA Indian Kashmir, two Christians arrested on false charges of forced conversions - Asia News |publisher=Asianews.it |date= |accessdate=2013-05-13}}</ref>}}\nChristians in India have frequently been subjected to intolerance,<ref name=autogenerated3 /> harassment, intimidation, and attacks by Muslims.<ref name=autogenerated6>{{cite web|last=Gheddo |first=Piero |url=http://www.asianews.it/news-en/Kashmir,-false-accusations-on-Facebook:-mob-tries-to-lynch-12-tourists-27053.html |title=INDIA Kashmir, false accusations on Facebook: mob tries to lynch 12 tourists - Asia News |publisher=Asianews.it |date= |accessdate=2013-05-15 |quote=The violent reaction was triggered by a [https://m.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=420992237981036&id=100002107914756&set=a.114711591942437.22089.100002107914756&ref=stream&_rdr photo] published on the Facebook page Gulmarg News.}}</ref> In [[Jammu and Kashmir]], a Christian convert and missionary, Bashir Tantray, was killed, allegedly by militant Islamists in 2006.<ref>[http://www.speroforum.com/site/article.asp?id=6705 Christian convert from Islam shot dead in Kashmir] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071017021324/http://www.speroforum.com/site/article.asp?id=6705 |date=17 October 2007 }},''SperoNews''.</ref>\n\nThe Government of Jammu-Kashmir in 2010 asked Jim Borst, a Dutch Catholic [[missionary]], who was at that time one of the two members of the Institute Mill Hill missionary in the Kashmir valley, to leave the valley. Borst was also in charge of two schools there.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gheddo |first=Piero |url=http://www.asianews.it/news-en/Missionary-forced-to-leave-Kashmir-because-his-schools-are-too-good-18910.html |title=INDIA Missionary forced to leave Kashmir because his schools are \"too good\" - Asia News |publisher=Asianews.it |date= |accessdate=2013-05-13}}</ref> Nevertheless, the spokesperson for Indian Christians, John Dayal rejected the claim that any forced conversion took place. John Dayal stated that a fact finding team interviewed Church personnel, the police, Ulema, school authorities and found no evidence of force or fraud conversions and each baptism has been proved to be voluntary\".<ref name=autogenerated5>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Fatwa-announced-against-Christian-schools-in-Kashmir-3-priests-asked-to-leave-valley/articleshow/11555784.cms |title='Fatwa' announced against Christian schools in Kashmir, 3 priests asked to leave valley - The Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date= |accessdate=2013-05-13}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2012, a [[Sharia]] court of Kashmir announced a [[Fatwa]] against Christian schools in Kashmir. It asked three priests to leave the valley on the charge that they were \"luring Muslims to Christianity\". The court not only instructed the government of Jammu and Kashmir to monitor such activities in the future but to also take over the management of the Christian missionary schools.<ref name=autogenerated5 />\n\nIn April 2012, a Christian couple was arrested with that accusation of \"promoting enmity\". The policemen later explained that the arrest was made \"as a precaution to prevent tensions in the area.\" However, their children told a completely different tale: \"Our parents went to Srinagar on April 16 last year to attend a wedding. The next day, while doing some shopping at the market, talking to a salesman our father said he was Christian and they were insulted, beaten and finally arrested by local police.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Gheddo |first=Piero |url=http://www.asianews.it/news-en/Indian-Kashmir:-Christians-arrested-for-promoting-enmity-24554.html |title=INDIA Indian Kashmir: Christians arrested for \"promoting enmity\" - Asia News |publisher=Asianews.it |date=2012-04-20 |accessdate=2013-05-13}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2012, unidentified arsonists, believed to be Muslim, [[church arson|set fire to a Catholic church]].<ref name=autogenerated4>{{cite web|last=Gheddo |first=Piero |url=http://www.asianews.it/news-en/Indian-Kashmir,-Muslims-set-fire-to-a-Catholic-church-24848.html |title=INDIA Indian Kashmir, \"unknown arsonists\" set fire to a Catholic church - Asia News |publisher=Asianews.it |date=2012-05-25 |accessdate=2013-05-13}}</ref> \n\nIn Srinagar, [[All Saints Church, Srinagar|All Saints Church]], a United Protestant parish belonging to the [[Church of North India]], and its parsonage, as well as the home of a Christian lady was also burned.<ref name=\"Singh2002\">{{cite web |last1=Singh |first1=Manpreet |title=India: Christians reach out to war-weary Muslims in Kashmir |url=https://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2002/september9/12.26.html |publisher=[[Christianity Today]] |accessdate=18 March 2020 |language=English}}</ref>\n\nConcerning these issues Father Mathew Thomas, pastor of Holy Family commented \"With these gestures, the Muslim community is trying to intimidate the Christian minority. But there are not even 400 Christians in Srinagar: I appeal to Omar Abdullah, chief minister, a Muslim who studied in Christian institutions. He must protect the entire population of Srinagar, including minorities.\"<ref name=autogenerated4 />\n\nA Muslim mob with the imprimatur of the local Imam, in April 2013, attacked a group of seven British Christians consisting of five women and two children, who were living in Shivpora for about four years. Stones were hurled at their vehicles and their house. The reason they claimed was to stop conversions to Christianity.<ref name=autogenerated3 />\n\nOn 5 February 2013, a crowd of people threw stones at the walls of the hotel where eight Americans and four South Koreans, who were accused of forcing conversion through a [[Facebook]] page, were staying. There were no injuries.<ref name=autogenerated6 /> The Facebook page of Gulmarg News showed an image of three oriental women and first line of a long caption stated, \"Attention Kashmir!!! Islam in Kashmir is under attack, Christians trying to convert Muslims.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asianews.it/news-en/Kashmir,-false-accusations-on-Facebook:-mob-tries-to-lynch-12-tourists-27053.html|title=Kashmir, false accusations on Facebook: mob tries to lynch 12 tourists|last=AsiaNews.it|website=www.asianews.it}}</ref>\n\n===Madhya Pradesh===\nOn 25 February 1995, [[Mariam Vattalil|Sister Rani Maria]], a [[nun]] working within the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Indore|Diocese of Indore]] was stabbed to death, allegedly for [[proselytising]] the tribals of Madhya Pradesh.<ref>{{cite news | title='We forgive you': How a Kerala nun's family embraced her murderer | url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/we-forgive-you-how-a-nun-s-family-embraced-her-murderer/story-DxwvsFds9KhtUoK7IHMN5I.html | date=2 August 2017 | work=[[Hindustan Times]]}}</ref> \n\nOn September 23, 1998, a group of about 18 or 20 armed men barged into a convent and [[Jhabua nuns rape case|gang raped four nuns in Jhabua]]. Christian groups accused religious fundamentalists for the attack. Later, the Vishva Hindu Parishad, accused the nuns of religious conversion. The former BJP MP, head of the Bajrang Dal and deputy head of the VHP, Baikunt Lal Sharma Prem said that the nuns were asking for it.<ref name=\":9\" /> \n\nA church was burned down and bibles were burnt in [[Mandla district]] in September 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bhopal/Church-set-ablaze-in-Mandla-district/articleshow/43715586.cms |title=Church set ablaze in Mandla district |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=September 28, 2014 |publisher=The Times of India |access-date=July 30, 2018}}</ref> In March 2015, a Bible convention was attacked in [[Jabalpur]], with allegations that religious conversions were taking place.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/church-attacked-in-jabalpur-christians-threaten-to-shut-down-schools-if-attackers-not-caught-748560 |title=Church Attacked in Jabalpur, Christians Threaten to Shut Schools if Attackers Not Caught |last=Das |first=Siddarth Ranjan |date=March 22, 2015 |publisher=[[NDTV]] |access-date=July 30, 2018}}</ref> Christian tribals were said to be living in fear with the rising incidence of attacks.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/fear-rules-in-tribal-pockets-of-madhya-pradesh-after-attack-on-churches-749343 |title=Fear Rules in Tribal Pockets of Madhya Pradesh After Attack on Churches |last=Das |first=Siddarth Ranjan |date=March 25, 2015 |publisher=NDTV |access-date=July 30, 2018}}</ref> On March 2020, A Pentecostal pastor was attacked with rods,chains and sticks and left with multiple fractures and head injuries in [[Sehore]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/madhya-pradesh-man-assaulted-over-forced-conversion-6307493/|title=Madhya Pradesh: Man assaulted over 'forced conversion'|date=2020-03-10|website=The Indian Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\nOn March 2015, Around 50 members belonging to Bajrang Dal and Dharam Sena attacked a church and two schools with slogans of \"Jai Shree Ram\" in Jabalpur. They vandalised the church's parish house,destroyed the pots and window panes and also attacked the people who had gathered there for a convention.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/church-catholic-school-christians-jabalpur-valdalised-bajrang-dal-245392-2015-03-22|title=Church, Catholic school vandalised in Madhya Pradesh|last=DelhiMarch 22|first=IndiaToday in New|last2=March 25|first2=2015UPDATED|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-03-21|last3=Ist|first3=2015 10:27}}</ref> More than a dozen people were injured and one was left critical by the attack.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/bhopal/mp-three-churches-attacked-in-jabalpur-police-inaction-irks-christians/article1-1329370.aspx|title=MP: Church, two schools attacked in Jabalpur|date=22 March 2015|website=hindustantimes.com}}</ref> The same cathedral had also been attacked by right-wing groups in 2008 and the entire altar was burnt down.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zeenews.india.com/news/madhya-pradesh/jabalpur-church-targeted-for-second-time-since-2008_1566379.html|title=Jabalpur church targeted for second time since 2008|date=23 March 2015|website=india.com}}</ref> \n\nOn December 2017, members of the militant group [[Bajrang Dal]] attacked a group of catholic carol singers in [[Satna district|Satna district]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thelogicalindian.com/news/right-wing-hindu-group-attack-carol-singers-satna-sets-priests-car-ablaze/|title=MP: Police Arrest 30 Carol Singers Singing On The Road, Right Wing Group Sets Priest's Car Ablaze|last=Mondal|first=Swarnami Mondal|date=2017-12-16|website=thelogicalindian.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref> The police detained the carol singers instead of the perpetrators and then the attackers attacked the christian students inside the police station and set fire to the priest's car outside.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sputniknews.com/asia/201712151060037235-carol-singers-india-arrested/|title=Christmas Carol Singers Arrested in India, Priests Under Attack From Hindu Mob|website=sputniknews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref>\n\n===Kerala===\n\nA Christian priest, K. K. Alavi in [[Manjeri]], a 1970 convert from Islam,<ref>\"[http://www.the-good-way.com/eng/books/7825/format-pdf IN SEARCH OF ASSURANCE]\" by K. K. Alavi</ref> thereby raised the ire of his former Muslim community and received many death threats. An Islamic group named \"The [[NDF India|National Development Front]]\" actively campaigned against him.<ref name=CE>[http://www.christianexaminer.com/Articles/Articles%20Jan06/Art_Jan06_07.html Convert from Islam in India Remains on Death List] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130511041409/http://www.christianexaminer.com/Articles/Articles%20Jan06/Art_Jan06_07.html |date=11 May 2013 }},'''Christian Examiner'''</ref> Muslim clerics are known to hold up Alavi as a prime example of an enemy of Islam even during prayers.<ref name=CE/> In that area traditional Christianity is considered blasphemy.<ref name=CE/>\n\nIn April 1998, a Church was attacked and it's crucifix desecrated.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nOn June 14 2015, around 30 RSS activists attacked two Pentecostal Churches in [[Attingal]]. The first attack injured the pastor and five others and the second attack injured ten congregants including a physically disabled person.<ref name=\":14\" />\n\nIn 2010, members of [[Popular Front of India]](PFI) [[Assault on T. J. Joseph|chopped off the hand of Professor T.J. Joseph]]. PFI alleged Joseph of committing blasphemy against [[Mohammed|prophet Mohammed]], based on a question paper he prepared for an exam..<ref>{{cite news|author=Special Correspondent |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/states/kerala/article536784.ece |title=No report yet on 'Taliban-model' courts: Kodiyeri |newspaper=The Hindu |date=2010-07-28 |accessdate=2013-05-13}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=http://newindianexpress.com/cities/kochi/article164133.ece |title=Controversial lecturer's palm chopped off |work=The New Indian Express |date=5 July 2010 |accessdate=12 May 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mathrubhumi.com/english/news.php?id=94349 |title=Attackers cut off Newman college prof Joseph's hand |publisher=Mathrubhumi |date=4 July 2010 |accessdate=12 May 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716073428/http://www.mathrubhumi.com/english/news.php?id=94349 |archivedate=16 July 2011 }}</ref> According to police, the attack was carried out by an eight-member team consisting of Savad of [[Asamannoor]], Pareeth of North Vazhakkulam, Shobin of [[Kothamangalam, Ernakulam|Kothamangalam]], Nazar of [[Aluva]], Shajil of [[Muvattupuzha]], Shamsuddin of [[Perumbavoor]], Shanvas and Jamal.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.manoramaonline.com/cgi-bin/MMOnline.dll/portal/ep/malayalamContentView.do?articleType=Malayalam+News&contentId=7767812&contentType=EDITORIAL&BV_ID=@@@ |title=Home |publisher=Manorama Online |accessdate=12 May 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120307175130/http://www.manoramaonline.com/cgi-bin/MMOnline.dll/portal/ep/malayalamContentView.do?articleType=Malayalam+News&contentId=7767812&contentType=EDITORIAL&BV_ID=@@@ |archive-date=7 March 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Karnataka===\n{{see also|2008 attacks on Christians in southern Karnataka}}\n\nOn July 17, 1998, The Bajrang Dal militants carried out a series of attacks against eleven Christian schools in various parts of Karnataka.<ref name=\":9\" /> On November 22 1998, RSS activists beat up the pastor and the worshipers of an Evangelical Church during a prayer service in [[Kulai (Suratkal)]].<ref name=\":9\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.csw.org.uk/1998/12/01/press/6/article.htm|title=India: Church latest target of violence in Indian state of Karnataka.|website=www.csw.org.uk|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> On November 1999, girls from the [[St. Joseph's Evening College, Bangalore|St. Joseph\u2019s Evening College,Bangalore]] were surrounded and physically attacked by a  local BJP MLA's supporters near [[Anekal]].<ref name=\":11\" />\n\nOn February 2002, Around 70 Hindutva nationalists armed with clubs and stones attacked the Holy Family Catholic Church in southern Karnataka which left several worshippers injured.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ecoi.net/en/document/1153247.html|title=Treatment of Christians by Hindus, particularly the treatment of Christians who have converted from Hinduism; and the protection available to them [IND39529.E]|last=Canada|first=Immigration and Refugee Board of|date=2002-09-12|website=www.ecoi.net|language=en|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\nThere was a wave of church bombings in the early 2000s by the once banned Islamic organisation [[Deendar Anjuman]] which alleged that Christianity was not an 'Indian' religion.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2008-11-28/bangalore/27920961_1_blasts-church-j-j-nagar | work=The Times Of India | title=Church blasts culprits may be sentenced today - The Times of India}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, there was a wave of attacks directed against [[Christian churches]] and prayer halls in [[Karnataka]] by the Hindu organisation [[Bajrang Dal]] around 2008.<ref>[http://archive.deccanherald.com/Content/Sep192008/scroll2008091990873.asp?section=frontpagenews UPA govt puts State on notice] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131226223258/http://archive.deccanherald.com/Content/Sep192008/scroll2008091990873.asp?section=frontpagenews |date=December 26, 2013 }} Deccan Herald - 19 September 2008</ref><ref>[http://www.deccanherald.com/content/21327/adoration-monastery-attack-pre-planned.html \u2018Adoration Monastery attack was pre-planned\u2019] ''[[Deccan Herald]]'' - 25 August 2010</ref> The violence started from 14 September 2008 when about 20 churches were vandalised in [[Mangalore]], [[Udupi]], [[Chikkamagaluru]], and in other districts of Karnataka.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.asianews.it/news-en/Karnataka:-20-churches-attacked,-Christians-accuse-police-of-inaction-13221.html|title=INDIA Karnataka: 20 churches attacked, Christians accuse police of inaction|last=AsiaNews.it|website=www.asianews.it|access-date=2016-03-06}}</ref> Minor violence was later reported from the border state of [[Kerala]]. [[B.S. Yeddyurappa]], the [[Chief Minister]] of Karnataka, said the attacks were provoked by conversions of [[Hindus]] to [[Christianity]]. He also alleged that a [[Protestant]] group had distributed literature which insulted Hindu gods. The Chief Minister however clarified that he was not defending the actions of those who attacked prayer halls and churches in Mangalore, Udupi and Chikmagalur on Sunday.<ref name=\"More church attacks in Karnataka\">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7621590.stm More church attacks in Karnataka] BBC - 17 September 2008</ref> Later, the Christian leaders denied it and commented that [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] (BJP) was inciting violence rather than working to calm the situation. On the other hand, the Central Government had strongly criticised and sent showcase notices to the state Government for not solving the issue effectively.<ref>[http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2008\\story_20-9-2008_pg4_13 India government warns state over anti-Christian attacks] {{dead link|date=February 2017|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}} Daily Times - 20 September 2008</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.asianews.it/news-en/Karnataka:-New-wave-of-violence-and-attacks-on-Christians.-Complicity-of-authorities-21265.html|title=INDIA Karnataka: New wave of violence and attacks on Christians. Complicity of authorities|last=AsiaNews.it|website=www.asianews.it|access-date=2016-03-22}}</ref>\n\nIncidents of mob attacks against [[Jehovah\u2019s Witnesses]]<ref name=\"articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2008-09-15/news/27737748_1_prayer-halls-bajrang-dal-jayapura-in-chikmagalur-district|title=Bajrang Dal cadre attacks churches in Karnataka|website=timesofindia-economictimes|access-date=2016-03-06}}</ref> have been reported with increasing frequency in Karnataka. The attackers gather in gangs of 20 to 50 individuals to intimidate small groups of Witnesses engaging in the Christian ministry that they are well known for.\n\nA church in [[Mangalore]] was attacked and Doors and window panes were damaged in February 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/mangalore-church-vandalised-modi-call-religious-tolerance/1/420837.html|title=Mangalore church vandalised days after Modi's call for tolerance|website=India Today}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/others-news/mangalore-church-attacked-days-after-pms-remarks-on-religious-tolerance-742220|title=Mangalore Church Attacked Days After PM's Remarks on Religious Tolerance|website=ndtv.com}}</ref> On March 2020, Members of the RSS raided a christian hospital and attacked 2 christian workers during a quarrel which started when a bible was found in one of the treatment rooms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theblaze.com/news/hindu-extremists-attack-christian-hospital-in-india-over-bible-in-room-persecution-watchdog-says|title=Hindu extremists attack Christian hospital in India over Bible in room, persecution watchdog says|date=2020-03-18|website=TheBlaze|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\n===Orissa===\n{{Main|Religious violence in Orissa}}\nIn a well-publicised case, [[Graham Staines]], an Australian Christian missionary, was burnt to death along with his sons Timothy (aged 10) and Philip (aged 6), while they were sleeping in his station wagon at Manoharpur village in [[Keonjhar district]] in [[Orissa, India|Orissa]] in January 1999. He was running the [[Evangelical Missionary Society of Mayurbhanj]], an Australian missionary society.<ref name=\"HRW\"/> In 2003, [[Dara Singh (murderer)|Dara Singh]] was sentenced to life in prison after being convicted of leading the gang responsible.<ref name=frontline>[http://www.frontline.in/static/html/fl2021/stories/20031024003902400.htm The Staines case verdict] V. Venkatesan, Frontline Magazine,  11\u201323 Oct 2003</ref>\n\nOn September 2, 1999, a Catholic Priest was shot by a bow and beaten up to death by fifteen people allegedly religious fundamentalists who later burned down the entire church in [[Keonjhar district]].<ref name=\":9\" />  \n\nAn outbreak of violence started on 24 December 2007 at Bamunigam village of [[Kandhamal District]] when local activists forcefully removed a Christmas decoration placed on a site traditionally used during [[Durga Puja]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tehelka.com/story_main37.asp?filename=Ne190108next_stop.asp |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120715034654/http://tehelka.com/story_main37.asp?filename=Ne190108next_stop.asp |url-status=dead |archive-date=15 July 2012 |publisher=Tehalka |title=Tehelka:: Free. Fair. Fearless:Next Stop Orissa |accessdate=8 September 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url= http://ncm.nic.in/pdf/orissa%20report.pdf | title= Report of the NCM visit to Orissa, 6\u20138 January 2008 |publisher=NCM |accessdate = 26 August 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2008, [[Swami Lakshmanananda]], a Hindu swami and VHP anti-conversion and reconversion activist, was attacked and killed, along with four associates by Maoist guerrillas.<ref>[http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/maoists-killed-lakshmanananda-say-orissa-police/article1358482.ece?ref=relatedNews Maoists killed Lakshmanananda, say Orissa Police], The Hindu, 17 October 2008.</ref> The violence that followed resulted in the death of some Christians. The violence later spread to more than 600 villages in 14 of the 30 districts in the state, resulting in 5,600 Christian houses burnt and 54,000 homeless. 38 Christian people were murdered, while 18,000 were injured. Human rights groups estimated 100 deaths, including women, disabled and children. 295 churches and places of worship were destroyed, along with 13 schools and colleges and 5 non-profit organisation offices.<ref>{{cite book |last=Osuri |first=Goldie |title=Religious Freedom in India: Sovereignty and (anti) Conversion |publisher=Routledge |year=2013 |isbn=978-0415665575 |p=39\u201340}}</ref>   As of 2015, the Christian victims were still awaiting justice and rehabilitation.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Editorial |title=Indulging the Hate-mongers |journal=[[Economic and Political Weekly]] |volume=XLIX |number=35 |date=30 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, 1999 a mob of 5,000 locals attacked Ranalai (PIN - 761 017) in Gajapati District and [[arson|set houses on fire]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.tehelka.com/story_main40.asp?filename=Ne130908HindutvasViolentHistory.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-02-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221170851/http://archive.tehelka.com/story_main40.asp?filename=Ne130908HindutvasViolentHistory.asp |archivedate=21 February 2014 }} Tehelka magazine Vol 5, Issue 36, Dated Sept 13, 2008</ref><ref>Volume 16 - Issue 8, Apr. 10 - 23, 1999, India's National Magazine from the publishers of THE HINDU</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.frontline.in/static/html/fl1608/16080360.htm|title=Another attack in Orissa|website=www.frontline.in}}</ref> and engaged in [[looting]]. Three people were injured. The [[Chief Minister (India)|CM]] of Odisha, Sri [[Giridhar Gamang]], visited the next day.\n\nDuring the [[Kandhamal riots]] of 2008, some small [[village]]s in rural areas were targeted by [[extremist]]s. They killed the [[pastor]] of Mukundapur, a small village in Gajapati District<ref>The Hindu, Aug 27, 2008</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/Violence-spreads-in-Orissa/article15290222.ece|title=Violence spreads in Orissa|date=27 August 2008|publisher=|via=www.thehindu.com|newspaper=The Hindu}}</ref>\n\nOn February 2019, A man was [[Decapitation|beheaded]] for leaving Hinduism and converting to Christianity in [[Nabarangpur district]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sabrangindia.in/article/man-beheaded-odisha-converting-christianity|title=Man beheaded in Odisha for converting to Christianity|date=2019-02-25|website=SabrangIndia|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n\n=== Telangana ===\nOn January 2016, around 40 Hindu nationalists beat up a pastor and his congregation members after they falsely accused him of conversion in the [[Nizamabad district|Nizamabad District]]. The attackers tore the pastor's clothes and tore and trampled on the bibles. According to locals, six people were hospitalised and a four-year-old girl's leg was broken.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/telangana/2016/mar/20/Telangana-Unknown-Miscreants-Burn-Down-Makeshift-Chapel-in-Nizamabad-913949.html|title=Telangana: Unknown Miscreants Burn Down Makeshift Chapel in Nizamabad|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\nOn March 2016, a make shift Chapel was burnt down by unknown attackers in Gopanpally, Nizamabad.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nOn October 2019, a fact-finding team consisting of several rights organisation reported 32 instances of attacks on Dalit Christians in the [[Yadadri Bhuvanagiri district]] for the past one year. The attacks included  churches being vandalised and attacks on pastors and their families by activists of the VHP, RSS and ABVP.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/communal-attacks-dalit-christians-rise-telanganas-yadadri-allege-activists-110748|title=Communal attacks on Dalit Christians on the rise in Telangana's Yadadri, allege activists|last=|first=|date=|website=www.thenewsminute.com|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> The activists reported that despite the attacks the police have not taken any action.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/telangana/2019/oct/18/attacks-on-dalit-christians-on-the-rise-in-yadadri-district-allege-rights-activists-2049307.html|title=Attacks on Dalit Christians on the rise in Yadadri district, allege rights activists|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\nOn 2nd October 2019, A mob of around 20 people chanting 'Jai Sree Ram' allegedly broke into a pastor's house when the family was celebrating their daughter's birthday party and attacked the pastor and abused his wife in Vasala Marri.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Andhra Pradesh ===\nIn April 1998, a Baptist Church in the [[Kurnool district]] was destroyed by VHP militants.<ref name=\":9\" /> \n\nOn June 23 2000, Crosses at 40 graves in a cemetery were desecrated in [[Rajahmundry]] and after four days another cemetery was vandalised in [[Vanasthalipuram]] allegedly by religious fundamentalists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rediff.com/%0D%0Anews/2000/jun/23grave1.htm|title=Christian cemetery desecrated in Andhra|last=|first=|date=|website=www.rediff.com|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rediff.com/news/2000/jun/27grave.htm|title=rediff.com: Another Christian cemetery vandalised in AP|website=www.rediff.com|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> On July 2000, three alleged Hindu Nationalists killed a priest in [[Guntur]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/857722.stm|title=BBC News {{!}} SOUTH ASIA {{!}} Priest killed in India|website=news.bbc.co.uk|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n=== Maharashtra ===\nOn February 1998, RSS activists Ransacked a Hospital in [[Latur]] run by the Indian Catholic Association.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.refworld.org/docid/3ae6a84b4.html|title=Refworld {{!}} Politics by Other Means: Attacks Against Christians in India|last=Refugees|first=United Nations High Commissioner for|website=Refworld|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> On October 1998, a prayer hall and  a prayer house in Nasik was attacked and destroyed.<ref name=\":9\" /> On December 25 1998, armed Bajrang Dal militants accosted about 1,000 attendees of a dance function at a christian school in [[Borivali]].<ref name=\":9\" /> \n\nOn June 1999, the [[Shiv Sena]] launched a series of attacks against Christian kindergarten schools, because the schools were allegedly not giving admission to the Children of the Shiv Sena activists. On June 26, attackers suspected to be Shiv Sena members attacked and vandalised the Sacred Heart school in [[Worli]].<ref name=\":9\" /><ref name=\":12\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=The politics behind anti Christian violence : a compilation of investigation committee reports into acts of violence against the Christian minorities|date=2006|publisher=Media House|others=Puniyani, Ram.|year=|isbn=81-7495-237-3|location=Delhi|pages=367-381|oclc=182969294}}</ref>\n\nOn April 1999, Unknown attackers destroyed a cross at a school run by nuns in [[Yavatmal]].<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rediff.com/news/2000/jun/27chur.htm|title=rediff.com: Church in Maharashtra town ransacked|website=www.rediff.com|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> On June 2000, a catholic church in [[Pusad]] was attacked and ransacked allegedly by fundamentalists.<ref name=\":7\" /> On March 2004, 6 Bajrang Dal militants were arrested for disrupting a private prayer meeting in [[Kopar Khairane]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mumbai/Six-held-for-disrupting-prayer-meeting/articleshow/555231.cms|title=Six held for disrupting prayer meeting - Times of India|website=The Times of India|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nOn March 2015, St. George church in [[Mumbai]] was attacked by masked persons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firstpost.com/mumbai/miscreants-attack-church-navi-mumbai-caught-cctv-footage-2166903.html|title=Masked men attack St George Catholic Church in Navi Mumbai, caught on CCTV footage - Firstpost|website=www.firstpost.com}}</ref> Four people were arrested by the police including a person who operated an illegal gambling den. The police claimed that it was a revenge attack because the accused suspected that a complaint from St. George's Church had led to a police raid on their gambling den.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/mumbai/navi-mumbai-church-attacked-after-raid-on-gambling-den/article1-1330443.aspx|title=Navi Mumbai church attacked after raid on gambling den|date=25 March 2015|website=hindustantimes.com}}</ref>\n\n15 members allegedly belonging to the Bharatiya Janata Party armed with swords, iron rods, knives and empty beer bottles attacked and threw stones at around 40 people offering prayers in a church at [[Kolhapur district]] on December 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/christian-gathering-attacked-during-sunday-prayers-in-maharashtra-oppn-blames-bjp-1417218-2018-12-25|title=Christian gathering attacked during Sunday prayers in Maharashtra, Oppn blames BJP|last=MumbaiDecember 25|first=Kamlesh Damodar Sutar Saurabh Vaktania|last2=December 26|first2=2018UPDATED|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18|last3=Ist|first3=2018 13:20}}</ref> Twelve people were injured and four people were hospitalised.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/cities/christian-gathering-attacked-during-sunday-prayers-in-maharashtra-village-1967913|title=Christian Gathering Attacked During Sunday Prayers In Maharashtra Village|website=NDTV.com|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n\n===Gujarat===\n{{See also|1998 attacks on Christians in southeastern Gujarat}}\nIn Gujarat, 22 churches were burnt or destroyed, and another 16 damaged in the year 1997 alone.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sscnet.ucla.edu/southasia/History/Current_Affairs/Current_affairs.html|title=Anti-Christian Violence in India}}</ref><ref name=\":12\" />Recently, there has been a sharp increase in violent attacks on Christians.\nA Hindu group claims to have converted 2,000 tribal Christians to Hinduism. The attackers had vandalised places of worship and thus caused strike terror among the tribals. On 18 September, the Central Government issued an advisory under Article 355 of the constitution to the Orissa government along with Karnataka.<ref name=\"Christian Today\">{{cite web|title=Hindu extremists convert 2,000 Christians in India|url=http://www.christiantoday.com/article/hindu.extremists.convert.2000.christians.in.india/15965.htm}}</ref>{{unreliable source?|date=April 2015}}\n\nDuring [[1998 attacks on Christians in southeastern Gujarat]], the Human Rights Watch reported more than 20 incidents of Churches, prayer halls being burnt down and damaged in and around the Dang District. The organisation also reported assaults against Christians, damages and burning down of Churches and Christian institutions in at least 25 villages all over Gujarat from December 25, 1998 to the next ten days.<ref name=\":10\" /> \n\nOn November 1997, Alleged VHP militants snatched the mic and shouted pro Hindu slogans during a prayer meeting at Lal Bahadur Shastri Stadium. They also cut the cables and damaged a van.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.indowindow.com/sad/article.php?child=27&article=23|title=Hindutva attacks against the Christian minority in India|website=www.indowindow.com|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> \n\nOn March 2 1998,  Members from VHP, Bajrang Dal and [[Durga Vahini]] beat up a Christian group which included foreign tourists distributing pamphlets for a prayer meeting on march 4th in the Baroda polo ground in Padra. They also made them chant the names of Hindu gods.<ref name=\":8\" /> Later, during the meeting at the Baroda polo ground on March 4th, around 300 VHP, Bajrang Dal militants ran amongst the audience creating panic and chaos by bursting fire crackers and blowing whistles. The assailants then went on to mercilessly beat up the audience, set ablaze a car and destroyed the musical instruments. They prevented the buses from taking off and the stranded people were again beaten up. Some people received severe head injuries including fractured hands. Earlier they even tried to set the stage on fire during it's construction. <ref name=\":8\" />\n\nOn April 1998, A Jacobite run school was vandalised and a Mary statue in the school was damaged on the pretext that Sanskrit was not taught there.<ref name=\":8\" /> On July 1998, alleged VHP militants dug out a Methodist christian from a cemetery and dumped the body near a [[Methodist church]] in Kapadvanj.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\nOn August 2000, a Priest was beaten up and made to walk naked through the town after he was reported to be distributing religious pamphlets in [[Surendranagar Dudhrej|Surendranagar]].<ref name=\":5\" /> On March 2002, a Christian Mission was ransacked and burned in [[Sanjeli]] by members of the RSS and VHP. <ref name=\":5\" />\n\n=== Chhattisgarh ===\nThe Indian Organization Persecution relief reported that there were 54 instances of attacks in 2016 when BJP was in power in Chattigarh and the number reduced to 21 when Congress took over the state in 2019.<ref name=\":0\" /> Chhattisgarh Christian Association president Arun Pannalal said  93 organised attacks on Christians were reported in the state between 2014 and 2015.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nOn June 2015, A Nun was allegedly tied and sexually assaulted in a hospital in Raipur.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Dahat|first=Pavan|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/nun-assaulted-in-raipur-hospital/article7337688.ece|title=Nun assaulted in Raipur hospital|date=2015-06-21|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-21|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\nOn March 6 2016, a group of more than 15-20 members of the militant organisation [[Bajrang Dal]] chanting \"Jai Shri Ram\" with saffron bands on their foreheads vandalised a church and attacked the people during the Sunday prayers in [[Raipur district]]. The members destroyed the chairs, fans and attacked the worshipers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-chhattisgarh-church-in-raipur-vandalized-by-mob-chanting-jai-sri-ram-2186136|title=Chhattisgarh: Church in Raipur vandalized by alleged Bajrang Dal mob, 5 injured|date=2016-03-06|website=DNA India|language=en|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> They attacked the women,ripped off their clothes and molested them. Bibles and the pictures hung on the walls were also desecrated and they also thrashed the infants.<ref>{{Cite news|last=ANI|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ani/raipur-church-attack-seven-people-surrender-before-police-116031600198_1.html|title=Raipur church attack: Seven people surrender before police|date=2016-03-16|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\nOn April 2016, Bajrang Dal militants thrashed a pastor,his 7 month pregnant wife and his children in [[Tokopal]]. The attackers kept a sword to the pastor's neck and forced him to say \"Jai Shree Ram\" and when he refused, the members poured petrol on the family and tried to set them ablaze. They also set fire to the church before escaping.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecitizen.in/index.php/en/NewsDetail/index/2/7533/A-7-month-Pregnant-Christian-Woman-Drenched-With-Petrol-by-Bajrang-Dal-Silence-of-the-Lambs|title=A 7-month Pregnant Christian Woman Drenched With Petrol by Bajrang Dal: Silence of the Lambs|last=chaudhary|first=shubhda|website=The Citizen|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> They allegedly destroyed the electronics and set the furniture and scriptures ablaze. The family managed to escape as the church burned.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/raipur/Pastor-pregnant-wife-assaulted-in-Chgarh/articleshow/51888310.cms|title=Pastor, pregnant wife assaulted in Chhattisgarh {{!}} Raipur News - Times of India|last=Apr 19|first=Rashmi Drolia {{!}} TNN {{!}} Updated|last2=2016|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-03-17|last3=Ist|first3=19:19}}</ref>\n\n=== Bihar ===\nIn the [[Gumla district]] two Catholic priests were killed and their skulls crushed on 1996. In October 1997, a decapitated, tortured cigarette-burnt body body of a catholic priest was found in the forests near Hazaribagh allegedly killed by Hindu nationalist groups.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/reports/1999/indiachr/christians8-03.htm#P152_24603|title=III. THE CONTEXT OF ANTI-CHRISTIAN VIOLENCE|last=|first=|date=|website=Human Rights Watch|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn September 20 1999, at [[Jalalpur, Bihar|Jalalpur]], a nun from Tamil Nadu was stripped,molested and forced to drink the urine of the attackers who also asked her why they have not fled, despite the violence against Christians all over the country.<ref name=\":11\" /> \n\nOn May 2001, Several bombs were set off by Hindu nationalists in a Catholic Cathedral in [[Muzaffarpur]]. The attackers left a note which indicated their concern when large number of tribals were embracing Christianity in [[Patna district]]. The note also stated that India is a Hindu Rashtra and Christians must leave India.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n=== Jharkhand ===\nOn April 2019, a mob alleged to be a Hindu vigilante group armed with iron rods and sticks attacked four tribal christian men who were accused of skinning a dead ox in. One man was killed and the other three were injured. Later investigation revealed the ox died naturally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/world/2019/04/479303/christian-man-beaten-death-latest-cow-lynching-india|title=Christian man beaten to death in latest 'cow lynching' in India|last=AFP|date=2019-04-14|website=NST Online|language=en|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\nOn September 2019, a group of 15-20 men attacked three tribal christian men for allegedly selling beef after the news spread through WhatsApp messages in [[Khunti district]]. One was killed and the other two were left critical in the attack.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theprint.in/india/mob-lynching-in-jharkhand-again-beaten-up-for-selling-beef-tribal-man-dead-2-critical/295283/|title=Mob lynching in Jharkhand again: Beaten up for 'selling beef', tribal man dead, 2 critical|last=Das|first=Madhuparna|date=2019-09-23|website=ThePrint|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n=== Rajasthan ===\nOn November 1997, VHP militants attacked Christian houses and threatened to leave the district within the next 3 years in [[Banswara district]].<ref name=\":8\" /> On January 2001, the All Indian christian Council alleged that  of the Bajrang Dal militants attacked two priests and their followers and ransacked the house of one of the priest.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n=== Uttarakhand ===\nA mob razed a church building and attacked the worshippers and their children in [[Khatima]] on 1992.<ref name=\":8\" /> On September 1998, members of the Bajrang Dal, Rana Tharu Parishad and [[Hindu Jagran Manch]] barged into a church and carried out prayers for two hours by placing an idol of Shiva inside the Union Church in Amaun, Udham Singh Nagar district.<ref name=\":9\" />\n=== Punjab ===\nOn 31st March 1998, A group of youth ransacked a congregation in Jalandhar. They damaged the lights and chairs and set the stage on fire which made more than a 100 people in the congregation flee in panic. The District BJP president justified the attacks and accused the preachers of trying to convert the people.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=Chandigarh edition|date=April 2, 1998|work=The Indian Express|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Haryana ===\nDuring the time of Easter in 2000, a series of attacks took place against Christian institutions in the towns of [[Karnal]], [[Sonipat]] and [[Panipat]]. On April 22 2000, 3 nuns on their way to an easter mass at [[Rewari]] were attacked and injured by suspected Hindutva group.<ref name=\":13\" />\n\nOn March 2015, a group vandalized a church under construction and replaced with its cross with a Hanuman idol and a flag of [[Rama]] in [[Haryana]]. It also alleged that the group, threatened the priest of murder and stole some a cooler and other items.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/north/story/church-vandalised-haryana-cross-hanuman-idol-244407-2015-03-15|title=Church vandalised in Haryana, cross replaced with Hanuman idol|last=March 15|first=IndiaToday in|last2=March 21|first2=2015UPDATED:|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03|last3=Ist|first3=2015 22:05}}</ref>\n\n=== West Bengal ===\n\nIn March 2015, a 71-year-old [[nun]] was gang raped in [[West Bengal]] during an attack on a convent school in which the school's chapel was ransacked and sacred items stolen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Nun-gang-raped-in-West-Bengal-Cops-detain-eight-people-for-interrogation/articleshow/46571061.cms|title=Nun gang-raped in West Bengal: Cops detain eight people for interrogation - Times of India \u25ba|website=indiatimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/03/14/india-nun-gang-rape_n_6869266.html | title=HuffPost is now a part of Verizon Media}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/cities/kolkata/archbishop-clears-mamata-blames-modi-govt-for-rising-violence-against-minorities/|title=Nun Gang Rape Case: Archbishop clears Mamata, blames Modi govt for rising violence against minorities|date=17 March 2015|website=indianexpress.com}}</ref> The Police identified all eight perpetrators and arrested six of them, two of whom were Bangladeshi nationals.<ref>[http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-ranaghat-gang-rape-case-police-detains-two-bangladesh-nationals-2070557 Ranaghat gang-rape case: Police detains two Bangladesh nationals], DNA India, 20 March 2015.</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-india-32143051 Indian nun rape case: Police make more arrests], BBC News, 1 April 2015.</ref><ref>[http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2015/04/suspects-nun-rape-case-indian-court-150403194634975.html Suspects in nun rape case appear in Indian court], Al Jazeera News, 3 April 2015.</ref>\n\nOn December 2019, members belonging to the RSS and BJP hurled [[Bomb|bombs]] at a church chanting \"[[Jai Shri Ram]]\" in the [[East Midnapore district]] during the Christmas celebrations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/3-held-for-attack-on-bengal-church/story-cg7rz0jOupuPnBi01tcuFI.html|title=3 held for attack on Bengal church|date=2020-12-30|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> The members attacked the people as they fled in panic and went on to desecrate the entire church. The members destroyed the furniture, ceiling fans, sound systems, window panes, microphones,the pastor's car and even the water tank.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.india.com/news/india/3-arrested-for-bomb-blast-vandalism-at-west-bengal-church-3893838/|title=3 Arrested For Bomb Blast, Vandalism at West Bengal Church|last=Desk|first=India com News|date=2019-12-30|website=India News, Breaking News, Entertainment News {{!}} India.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> Four persons, including two children, were injured in the attack.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/3-arrested-for-throwing-bombs-at-bengal-church-vandalising-property-2156211|title=3 Arrested For Throwing Bombs At Bengal Church, Vandalising Property|website=NDTV.com|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>{{Persecutions of the Catholic Church sidebar}}\n\n==Response==\n===US State Department===\nIn its annual human rights reports for 1999, the [[United States Department of State]] criticised India for \"increasing societal violence against Christians.\"<ref name=\"Expressindia\">{{cite web|title=US rights report slams India for anti-Christian violence|url=http://www.expressindia.com/news/ie/daily/19990227/ige27064.html|date=27 February 1999|accessdate=17 December 2007}}</ref> The report on anti-Christian violence listed over 90 incidents of anti-Christian violence, ranging from damage of religious property to violence against Christians pilgrims. The incidents listed in the report were attributed to local media reports and information gathered by Christian groups in India.<ref name=\"Expressindia\"/>\n\n===National Commission for Minorities===\nAfter the [[2008 attacks on Christians in southern Karnataka]] by [[Bajrang Dal]] and [[Sri Ram Sena]] activists, the [[National Commission for Minorities]] accused the Karnataka government of serious lapses in handling the situation. They were found directly responsible for allowing the violence to spread, and claimed the police failed to solve the issue effectively as the violence continues. They also clarified that there were no reported complaints of forced conversion registered in the state.<ref name=\"ptinews.com\"/><ref name=\"mangalorean.com\"/>\n\n===National Integration Council of India===\nOn 13 October 2008, the [[National Integration Council]] of India called a special meeting chaired by [[Manmohan Singh]], then Prime Minister of India, where he condemned the violence  of Hindu militant organisations such as Bajrang Dal, VHP etc.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}} The prime minister had earlier publicly admitted that the ongoing violence against the Christian communities was a matter of great \"national shame\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/Editorial/India_under_siege_/articleshow/3610403.cms |title=India under siege |publisher=Economictimes.indiatimes.com |date=18 October 2008 |accessdate=29 April 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Vatican===\nOn 12 October 2008, [[Pope Benedict XVI]] criticised the continuing anti-Christian violence in India.\n\nOn 28 October, the [[Holy See|Vatican]] called upon the memory of [[Mahatma Gandhi]] for an end to the religious violence in Orissa. In a written address to Hindus, the Vatican office said Christian and Hindu leaders needed to foster a belief in [[non-violence]] among followers.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://in.reuters.com/article/topNews/idINIndia-36186520081028 |title=Vatican invokes Gandhi in plea to end Orissa violence |publisher=In.reuters.com |date=28 October 2008 |accessdate=29 April 2010}}</ref> Although the Mahatma had been strong in his opposition to forced conversion and Christian missionary activities, he had denounced violence as an appropriate response.<ref>Conversion: Old Worlds and New, p. 273,  Kenneth Mills, Anthony Grafton, University Rochester Press, quote= \"Furthermore, Gandhi's famous distrust of Christian missionaries and Christian conversions offered a screen.\"</ref><ref>Gandhi's Pilgrimage of Faith: From Darkness to Light, Uma Majmudar, p.119, Suny Press, quote=\"Gandhi also disapproved of schools run by the Christian Missionaries because of their Western bias.\"</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india/his-faith-our-faith/story-sdpOimN69y2gTuSJs1SltI.html |title=His faith, our faith |publisher=Hindustan Times |date=29 January 2008 |accessdate=29 April 2010|quote=From these two beliefs followed the third, which was that Gandhi rejected conversion and missionary work.}}</ref><ref>http://www.mkgandhi.org/ebks/gandhiji-on-religious-conversion.pdf</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Religious violence in India]]\n* [[Violence against Muslims in India]]\n* [[Religion in India]]\n* [[Persecution of Christians]]\n* [[Persecution of Hindus]]\n* [[Communalism (South Asia)]]\n* [[Hindutva]]\n* [[Saffron terror]]\n* [[Christian terrorism]]\n* [[1998 attacks on Christians in southeastern Gujarat]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Bauman |first=Chad M. |title=Hindu-Christian Conflict in India: Globalization, Conversion and the Coterminal Castes and Tribes |journal=The Journal of Asian Studies |volume=72 |pages=633\u2013653 |number=3 |date=August 2013 |url=http://digitalcommons.butler.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1271&context=facsch_papers |doi=10.1017/s0021911813000569}}\n* {{cite book |last=Osuri |first=Goldie |title=Religious Freedom in India: Sovereignty and (anti) Conversion |publisher=Routledge |year=2013 |isbn=978-0415665575}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Uma |first1=Saumya |last2=Grover |first2=Vrinda |title=Kandhamal: The Law must Change its Course |publisher=MARG: Multiple Action Research Group |location=New Delhi |year=2010 | isbn= 978-81-87377-19-1 |url=http://works.bepress.com/saumyauma/31/}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Asia in topic|Violence against Christians in}}\n\n[[Category:Christianity in India]]\n[[Category:Religiously motivated violence in India]]\n[[Category:Anti-Christian sentiment in Asia]]\n[[Category:Violence against Christians]]\n[[Category:Violence against Christians in India| ]]\n", "name_user": "Neils51", "label": "safe", "comment": "spelling - it's->its,typo(s) fixed: christian \u2192 Christian (9), easter \u2192 Easter, 7 month \u2192 7-month, a Baptist Church \u2192 a Baptist church", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Violence_against_Christians_in_India"}
{"title_page": "1916 North Carolina A&M Aggies football team", "text_new": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n |year = 1916\n |team = North Carolina A&M Aggies\n |image = \n |image_size = \n |conference = South Atlantic Intercollegiate Athletic Association\n |short_conf = SAIAA\n |record = 2-5\n |conf_record = \n |head_coach = [[Brit Patterson]]\n |hc_year = 1st \n |stadium = [[Riddick Stadium]]\n |captain = \n |champion = \n}}\n{{1916 SAIAA football standings}}\nThe '''1916 North Carolina A&M Aggies football team''' represented the [[NC State Wolfpack football|North Carolina A&M Aggies]] of [[North Carolina State University|North Carolina College of Agriculture and Mechanic Arts]] during the [[1916 college football season]]. In Brit Patterson's first season with the Aggies, the fledgling coach had to grapple with a number of blowout losses to Davidson, Virginia Tech, Navy, and Washington & Lee.  The team was also whipped, 5-61, against Georgetown college in the worst defeat in school history up to that point.  The Aggies were outscored 191 to 24 against their 7 opponents.\n\n==Schedule==\n{{CFB schedule\n\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 30\n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = yes\n| opponent = [[Roanoke Maroons|Roanoke]]\n| site_stadium = [[Riddick Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Raleigh, North Carolina|Raleigh, NC]]\n| score = 13-3\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 7\n| w/l = l\n| nonconf = no\n| opponent = Davidson\n| site_stadium = \n| site_cityst = [[Davidson, North Carolina|Davidson, NC]]\n| score = 0-16\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 19\n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = yes\n| opponent = [[1916 Wake Forest Baptists football team|Wake Forest]]\n| site_stadium = \n| site_cityst = [[Winston-Salem, North Carolina|Winston-Salem, NC]]\n| score = 6-0\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 28\n| w/l = l\n| nonconf = yes\n| opponent = [[1916 Virginia Tech Hokies fo